We'll take firewood and...

523
00:23:15,060 --> 00:23:16,460
(I'm getting firewood and the fire steel.)

524
00:23:16,460 --> 00:23:18,500
- Fire steel...
- Just one more round.

525
00:23:18,530 --> 00:23:20,670
No. Not anymore.

526
00:23:21,230 --> 00:23:23,100
- We definitely need fire.
- Definitely.

527
00:23:23,540 --> 00:23:25,170
We'll buy those.

528
00:23:25,340 --> 00:23:27,870
We won't be using these,
so we'll use them for the fire.

529
00:23:30,380 --> 00:23:31,710
Are you going to reuse these?

530
00:23:32,150 --> 00:23:33,750
Let's take everything that's made of wood.

531
00:23:35,350 --> 00:23:37,420
We were thinking of eating pork belly,

532
00:23:37,420 --> 00:23:38,750
pizza, and everything.

533
00:23:38,750 --> 00:23:41,420
In the end, all we got was firewood.

534
00:23:41,920 --> 00:23:43,560
This is why you should never gamble.

535
00:23:43,720 --> 00:23:45,230
But I won.

536
00:23:45,230 --> 00:23:47,090
You did, but look where we ended up.

537
00:23:47,260 --> 00:23:49,560
We could buy three sleeping bags.

538
00:23:50,330 --> 00:23:52,670
- I don't need one!
- We...

539
00:23:52,970 --> 00:23:55,270
I was sure
that we had three sleeping bags.

540
00:23:55,640 --> 00:23:57,540
Now, we have to sleep with nothing.

541
00:23:58,000 --> 00:23:59,640
I was picturing myself in a sleeping bag.

542
00:23:59,770 --> 00:24:01,340
This is bad.

543
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:03,540
You should know when to stop.

544
00:24:03,680 --> 00:24:05,210
I've told them time and time again.

545
00:24:05,810 --> 00:24:08,010
Firewood, a fire steel,

546
00:24:08,450 --> 00:24:10,250
and three sleeping bags.

547
00:24:10,420 --> 00:24:12,350
Imagine the warmth by the bonfire.

548
00:24:12,450 --> 00:24:13,950
Darn it.

549
00:24:14,350 --> 00:24:15,660
We got lost in gambling.

550
00:24:15,820 --> 00:24:17,660
We were literally money bugs.

551
00:24:18,290 --> 00:24:21,030
We were wandering idly,
just like that money bug.

552
00:24:21,190 --> 00:24:23,560
We earned nothing.
All we got was the cold.

553
00:24:24,960 --> 00:24:28,130
Isn't this the first time for any player
to sleep in such a poor environment?

554
00:24:28,500 --> 00:24:29,940
Everyone else seemed to get something.

555
00:24:30,470 --> 00:24:32,740
We're practically homeless beggars.

556
00:24:33,240 --> 00:24:35,780
How are we supposed to sleep here?
It makes no sense we have to sleep here.

557
00:24:36,280 --> 00:24:37,340
I said...

558
00:24:37,810 --> 00:24:40,510
I said we should stop there.

559
00:24:44,320 --> 00:24:47,290
I wish I could at least warm my feet up.
My feet are freezing right now.

560
00:24:47,290 --> 00:24:49,960
If we build a fire,
we can dry off our feet.

561
00:24:50,860 --> 00:24:53,960
Then let's grill some garlic for a snack.

562
00:24:54,230 --> 00:24:55,460
Sounds good. We have a lot of garlic.

563
00:24:55,730 --> 00:24:57,030
Where are the potatoes?

564
00:24:57,230 --> 00:24:58,900
- Oh, we sold them.
- We sold all the potatoes.

565
00:25:00,030 --> 00:25:01,200
Darn it.

566
00:25:02,000 --> 00:25:04,600
I've been very optimistic lately.

567
00:25:04,600 --> 00:25:07,070
I've been doing well
without having any negative thoughts.

568
00:25:07,270 --> 00:25:08,640
Thank you, Bloody Game X.

569
00:25:08,780 --> 00:25:12,310
I felt so alive,
able to feel my heart still beating.

570
00:25:12,710 --> 00:25:14,480
I realized I wanted to backstab them.

571
00:25:16,850 --> 00:25:19,050
- What is it?
- The delivery is here. I'll go get it.

572
00:25:19,150 --> 00:25:20,390
- It's probably the firewood.
- It must be the firewood.

573
00:25:21,590 --> 00:25:23,020
Let's build a fire now.

574
00:25:23,720 --> 00:25:25,060
How about we use this as kindling?

575
00:25:25,060 --> 00:25:27,160
Yes. I think we can use this.

576
00:25:27,160 --> 00:25:29,830
(They will try to build a fire
using a fire steel.)

577
00:25:41,310 --> 00:25:42,440
- Okay. We started a fire.
- We've got a fire going.

578
00:25:43,780 --> 00:25:44,910
Give me some paper.

579
00:25:46,480 --> 00:25:47,550
Okay.

580
00:25:53,620 --> 00:25:55,490
It's good enough.
The fire will get bigger.

581
00:25:59,760 --> 00:26:01,260
(Sighing in satisfaction)

582
00:26:01,260 --> 00:26:02,360
I feel much better now.

583
00:26:06,670 --> 00:26:07,670
Oh, garlic.

584
00:26:08,570 --> 00:26:11,240
We're warming out feet up
while grilling garlic.

585
00:26:13,440 --> 00:26:14,870
This is basically a survival game.

586
00:26:17,440 --> 00:26:19,680
- It'll be ready shortly.
- The garlic smells so good.

587
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:23,420
- Can you smell the garlic?
- Yes, I can.

588
00:26:23,450 --> 00:26:25,290
- It smells so good.
- Right? It's no joke.

589
00:26:27,590 --> 00:26:28,720
Do you like garlic?

590
00:26:30,690 --> 00:26:32,030
- Smell the garlic.
- I like having garlic with some meat.

591
00:26:32,030 --> 00:26:33,160
(Sniffing)

592
00:26:33,490 --> 00:26:34,530
I wanted you to smell the garlic.

593
00:26:36,960 --> 00:26:38,600
The garlic smells amazing. Oh, my.

594
00:26:38,600 --> 00:26:42,170
We're smelling the garlic
while drying our feet.

595
00:26:42,700 --> 00:26:44,300
It looks very delicious.

596
00:26:44,770 --> 00:26:46,070
It smells so tasty.

597
00:26:49,580 --> 00:26:50,910
Gwan Hee, this is nice.

598
00:26:54,050 --> 00:26:55,880
Look at that. The garlic is dancing.

599
00:26:56,850 --> 00:26:57,980
One, two, three...

600
00:26:58,220 --> 00:26:59,920
- I peeled exactly 8 cloves of garlic...
- We have exactly 8 cloves.

601
00:26:59,920 --> 00:27:01,920
- so each of us could have two.
- You can have mine.

602
00:27:02,460 --> 00:27:03,690
- I'm good.
- Come on.

603
00:27:03,690 --> 00:27:06,260
You should eat some.
We're a team, you know.

604
00:27:06,260 --> 00:27:08,960
Really? But I don't want my breath
to smell like garlic, just as my hands do.

605
00:27:09,460 --> 00:27:11,930
- We should share it as a team.
- I think it's ready.

606
00:27:12,870 --> 00:27:13,930
- Go ahead and have some first.
- Thanks.

607
00:27:16,170 --> 00:27:17,870
(It's so hot.)

608
00:27:18,240 --> 00:27:19,240
Isn't it hot?

609
00:27:20,470 --> 00:27:21,470
Is it good?

610
00:27:22,010 --> 00:27:23,080
It's good.

611
00:27:24,540 --> 00:27:25,550
- Is it good?
- Yes.

612
00:27:27,610 --> 00:27:28,880
That's good. Yes.

613
00:27:30,620 --> 00:27:31,850
- Amazing.
- It melts in my mouth.

614
00:27:31,850 --> 00:27:32,890
It's good.

615
00:27:32,990 --> 00:27:34,050
Don't touch the metal.

616
00:27:34,420 --> 00:27:35,490
Hold on a second.

617
00:27:37,720 --> 00:27:39,860
(He uses his cap as a plate
to prevent her from burning her hand.)

618
00:27:40,130 --> 00:27:42,200
He wore that cap all day long.

619
00:27:42,260 --> 00:27:44,330
Do you think it's clean?

620
00:27:47,000 --> 00:27:48,300
- We have...
- It's okay.

621
00:27:48,300 --> 00:27:50,900
totally thrown hygiene out the window.

622
00:27:53,170 --> 00:27:56,640
Watching myself getting used to this
and becoming happy about the situation...

623
00:27:59,980 --> 00:28:02,750
The grilled garlic, in a situation
where we had nothing else to eat,

624
00:28:02,750 --> 00:28:06,420
was so amazing
that it could be on a restaurant menu.

625
00:28:06,590 --> 00:28:11,120
It's the best food
that has a rich flavor, aroma, and umami.

626
00:28:11,390 --> 00:28:12,660
I realized
that was why it was called super food.

627
00:28:13,030 --> 00:28:14,930
How do we sleep here?

628
00:28:15,360 --> 00:28:16,360
Before going to sleep...

629
00:28:16,360 --> 00:28:19,370
We should hit each other on the head
with the shovel.

630
00:28:19,830 --> 00:28:21,830
- To make us pass out?
- We need to pass out to sleep.

631
00:28:22,670 --> 00:28:26,110
You get hit hard on the head,
and then you'll wake up tomorrow morning.

632
00:28:27,910 --> 00:28:30,480
The last person awake will suffer,
but we have no choice.

633
00:28:30,710 --> 00:28:32,880
How are we supposed to sleep here?
It's ridiculous.

634
00:28:37,020 --> 00:28:39,450
Gosh. What should we do?

635
00:28:39,590 --> 00:28:41,150
I'm so worried about tonight.

636
00:28:43,560 --> 00:28:46,890
Just as you would expect,
after building a fire,

637
00:28:46,930 --> 00:28:50,560
everyone seemed to become quite drowsy.

638
00:28:51,330 --> 00:28:53,570
Let's do really well tomorrow.

639
00:28:56,700 --> 00:28:58,340
I think it will become fun tomorrow.

640
00:28:58,570 --> 00:29:00,240
It's either kill or get killed.

641
00:29:00,740 --> 00:29:03,540
From here on out, it's either go home
or send someone else home.

642
00:29:04,240 --> 00:29:07,550
Tomorrow,
I'm going to completely crush the team...

643
00:29:07,980 --> 00:29:09,420
with Choi Hye Seon and Hong Jin Ho.

644
00:29:09,480 --> 00:29:10,720
I'm not planning
to go after any other team.

645
00:29:10,780 --> 00:29:14,050
Obviously,
the other teams think of my team...

646
00:29:14,120 --> 00:29:15,460
as the weakest.

647
00:29:16,120 --> 00:29:17,290
But I'm confident we'll do well.

648
00:29:36,080 --> 00:29:37,740
As a result of the Money Challenge,

649
00:29:37,910 --> 00:29:41,350
Teams P1, P2, and Challenger...

650
00:29:41,780 --> 00:29:44,320
must vote
to send one elimination candidate...

651
00:29:44,320 --> 00:29:46,750
to the Deathmatch.

652
00:29:48,090 --> 00:29:50,590
Only one player will be eliminated today.

653
00:29:51,390 --> 00:29:55,230
The player who lost in the Deathmatch
will be the first to go home...

654
00:29:55,800 --> 00:29:59,230
and will never get
to return to Bloody Game X.

655
00:30:00,070 --> 00:30:02,670
Today's Deathmatch game
the elimination candidates will play...

656
00:30:02,840 --> 00:30:07,110
requires quick decision-making
and spatial awareness.

657
00:30:07,310 --> 00:30:10,840
Today, each team will select
their elimination candidate internally,

658
00:30:11,210 --> 00:30:13,710
so you cannot purchase extra vote tickets.

659
00:30:15,110 --> 00:30:17,580
The voting will end in one hour.

660
00:30:18,990 --> 00:30:21,720
(The voting begins.)

661
00:30:22,560 --> 00:30:23,890
Quick decision-making?

662
00:30:24,120 --> 00:30:25,160
I'll do it.

663
00:30:28,090 --> 00:30:30,260
It's only right for me to do it.

664
00:30:33,670 --> 00:30:36,370
Everything went wrong because of me.

665
00:30:37,800 --> 00:30:39,740
Let's think about it more
since we still have an hour.

666
00:30:39,770 --> 00:30:41,640
I was the one responsible for the outcome.

667
00:30:42,240 --> 00:30:45,340
I thought we placed last because of me...

668
00:30:45,550 --> 00:30:48,950
because I was the one who suggested
how we should play the game,

669
00:30:49,380 --> 00:30:51,250
and things went wrong for us.

670
00:30:52,120 --> 00:30:54,850
So I thought I should be the one
going to the Deathmatch.

671
00:30:55,390 --> 00:30:56,890
Let's feed them some misinformation.

672
00:30:57,420 --> 00:31:00,590
I think the winning team will select
the elimination candidates.

673
00:31:01,060 --> 00:31:02,900
No. I'm sure you misheard it.

674
00:31:03,160 --> 00:31:06,600
(Sang Min deployed a strategy
of tricking them with a fake rule.)

675
00:31:06,800 --> 00:31:09,670
(And it left Team P1 isolated.)

676
00:31:09,940 --> 00:31:13,270
To be honest, when Sang Min said
he would go to the Deathmatch,

677
00:31:14,010 --> 00:31:15,980
I thought it was right for him to go...

678
00:31:15,980 --> 00:31:18,850
because he was the biggest reason
for our defeat.

679
00:31:19,580 --> 00:31:22,750
Or how about this?
You go to the Deathmatch,

680
00:31:22,850 --> 00:31:24,420
just avoid placing last,

681
00:31:24,420 --> 00:31:28,350
and win the other three players over
to our side.

682
00:31:28,860 --> 00:31:30,790
- That'd be perfect.
- That's possible.

683
00:31:30,890 --> 00:31:33,130
- If...
- You're good at winning people over.

684
00:31:33,130 --> 00:31:34,390
Sang Min is the best
at dealing with people.

685
00:31:34,390 --> 00:31:38,160
The others will resent their teammates
just as you said.

686
00:31:38,430 --> 00:31:41,830
You can win them over
by telling them our team is solid.

687
00:31:42,270 --> 00:31:45,340
If you could come back with some allies,

688
00:31:45,340 --> 00:31:47,410
it'd be very helpful for our team.

689
00:31:48,070 --> 00:31:49,580
- Exactly.
- That's the best-case scenario.

690
00:31:49,980 --> 00:31:52,910
It'd be great
if he could come back with some allies.

691
00:31:59,420 --> 00:32:01,450
(Sang Min enters the Voting Room first.)

692
00:32:01,450 --> 00:32:03,560
Oh, hello. Thank you for your hard work.

693
00:32:04,620 --> 00:32:07,060
Please use your team's voting ticket
to vote.

694
00:32:08,690 --> 00:32:11,960
(1. Lee Sang Min, 2. Jeong Keun Woo,
3. Park Ji Min, 4. Lee Tae Gyun)

695
00:32:40,160 --> 00:32:43,230
(Team P1 has finished voting.)

696
00:32:44,060 --> 00:32:46,400
Whether it's a 3-way or a 4-way matchup,

697
00:32:47,170 --> 00:32:48,900
if you lose, you go home.

698
00:32:49,140 --> 00:32:52,310
Whoever goes to the Deathmatch,
let's save him next time.

699
00:32:53,210 --> 00:32:56,880
Seung Jin, you've never gone
to the Deathmatch before.

700
00:32:56,880 --> 00:32:59,050
No, I haven't. Just as I told you earlier,

701
00:33:00,110 --> 00:33:02,210
I have poor spatial awareness,
so I'm bad at directions.

702
00:33:02,650 --> 00:33:04,520
And that's why I'm not confident.

703
00:33:05,320 --> 00:33:06,790
This is what I'm worst at.

704
00:33:06,790 --> 00:33:09,560
I have such poor spatial awareness,
so I'm terrible at directions.

705
00:33:09,990 --> 00:33:12,360
- It's true.
- If it's a similar game to that...

706
00:33:12,390 --> 00:33:15,960
The Deathmatch game requires
spatial awareness of all things.

707
00:33:16,260 --> 00:33:18,760
Guess what Seung Jin said in a second.

708
00:33:19,600 --> 00:33:22,500
"I'm terrible at directions."
That's what he said.

709
00:33:22,500 --> 00:33:23,740
"I'm not bad at games like this."

710
00:33:24,140 --> 00:33:26,940
"Can somebody please stop me
from going to the Deathmatch?"

711
00:33:26,940 --> 00:33:29,510
"I can't do it."
That's how I took his comment.

712
00:33:29,810 --> 00:33:33,580
If I go to the Deathmatch,
I will do my best.

713
00:33:33,850 --> 00:33:35,210
You just have to beat one of them.

714
00:33:35,950 --> 00:33:38,280
If you just don't tense up,

715
00:33:38,280 --> 00:33:40,890
- I'm sure you'll pull it off.
- Sure. I won't tense up.

716
00:33:41,590 --> 00:33:43,860
I was nervous, but I wasn't worried.

717
00:33:44,390 --> 00:33:46,290
That helped me the most.

718
00:33:48,160 --> 00:33:50,930
- Let's go for a smoke.
- Okay. Let's go.

719
00:33:56,470 --> 00:33:57,940
I'm going to take a break too.

720
00:34:00,770 --> 00:34:01,840
What should we do?

721
00:34:04,880 --> 00:34:08,710
I can't tell how things will turn out
right now.

722
00:34:09,480 --> 00:34:12,550
Jin Hyeong would never volunteer
to go to the Deathmatch.

723
00:34:13,390 --> 00:34:16,890
Even when he made a mistake
and answered 1.42 million,

724
00:34:16,890 --> 00:34:18,590
he put the blame on Fujii Mina.

725
00:34:20,490 --> 00:34:24,000
What do you think? Since we have an hour,

726
00:34:24,000 --> 00:34:26,170
shall we open up and talk to Jin Hyeong?

727
00:34:27,670 --> 00:34:28,670
(Will they send him to the Deathmatch
by voting for him secretly?)

728
00:34:28,670 --> 00:34:30,000
He'll throw a fit if we do that.

729
00:34:30,100 --> 00:34:31,240
It'd be lame if we secretly voted for him.

730
00:34:31,500 --> 00:34:34,470
In my opinion, we should just talk to him.

731
00:34:37,510 --> 00:34:38,540
- Should we?
- Yes.

732
00:34:38,940 --> 00:34:41,510
Wait, no.
Let's go for a smoke without them.

733
00:34:42,250 --> 00:34:43,350
That'd be lame too.

734
00:34:46,790 --> 00:34:48,550
- Are you worried?
- Sorry?

735
00:34:49,890 --> 00:34:51,290
I'm not worried.

736
00:34:51,290 --> 00:34:53,560
I don't understand
why the other teams look down on you.

737
00:34:55,060 --> 00:34:58,800
We discussed only for five minutes,
and he said, "You can pull it off."

738
00:34:58,900 --> 00:35:01,300
Such comments made him look cheeky.

739
00:35:01,370 --> 00:35:02,640
- Right.
- Right?

740
00:35:02,640 --> 00:35:03,870
He said that while fully knowing that
Seung Jin would lose.

741
00:35:04,040 --> 00:35:06,770
- Exactly.
- We all know he'll lose.

742
00:35:07,140 --> 00:35:10,810
(Jin Hyeong is looking
for Sung Joo and YunB.)

743
00:35:11,180 --> 00:35:12,340
They went down.

744
00:35:12,480 --> 00:35:13,880
- Sorry?
- The two of them went down.

745
00:35:14,210 --> 00:35:16,220
I guess they're trying to figure out
the other teams' Deathmatch picks.

746
00:35:17,680 --> 00:35:19,820
I think it's best that we just...

747
00:35:20,150 --> 00:35:21,520
vote for him.

748
00:35:23,420 --> 00:35:25,520
We can deal with the consequences later.

749
00:35:26,190 --> 00:35:27,460
But we need Seung Jin to agree with us.

750
00:35:27,560 --> 00:35:29,230
- Right.
- But Seung Jin actually...

751
00:35:29,230 --> 00:35:31,960
If he disagrees, and the voting results in
a 2-to-2 tie, it'll be a disaster.

752
00:35:32,260 --> 00:35:33,970
- It'll be a total disaster.
- We'll fight like crazy.

753
00:35:33,970 --> 00:35:35,470
- It'll be a total disaster.
- Right.

754
00:35:36,840 --> 00:35:38,170
- It's dirty to do that behind his back.
- Yes.

755
00:35:38,170 --> 00:35:39,740
It's indeed dirty to vote for him
behind his back.

756
00:35:39,770 --> 00:35:41,440
If we're really going to do this,

757
00:35:41,640 --> 00:35:44,240
we should make sure that
Seung Jin agrees to vote for him.

758
00:35:47,680 --> 00:35:49,780
Both of us saw
how cutthroat Jin Hyeong could be...

759
00:35:49,780 --> 00:35:53,220
when we were on the second season
of the show.

760
00:35:53,490 --> 00:35:55,520
We tried to figure out...

761
00:35:55,520 --> 00:35:58,790
how to help him pull himself together
or how to punish him.

762
00:35:58,790 --> 00:36:00,490
Sending him to the Deathmatch means...

763
00:36:01,130 --> 00:36:03,000
that he can be eliminated.

764
00:36:03,000 --> 00:36:07,300
We're sending him to the Deathmatch
because he deserves it.

765
00:36:07,630 --> 00:36:09,030
So we decided to be bad guys...

766
00:36:09,030 --> 00:36:12,170
to help him pay for his past wrongdoings.

767
00:36:12,240 --> 00:36:14,270
YunB and I have made up our minds.

768
00:36:14,570 --> 00:36:18,280
The timing was just right.
When we sat down on the sofa...

769
00:36:19,410 --> 00:36:22,920
Be honest with me.
Do you think Seung Jin can...

770
00:36:23,920 --> 00:36:27,050
- Do I think he can win?
- I don't think he has a good chance.

771
00:36:27,050 --> 00:36:28,490
He doesn't have a good chance,

772
00:36:28,490 --> 00:36:30,290
- but only one player will be eliminated.
- Yes.

773
00:36:30,620 --> 00:36:33,790
But still, in my opinion,
he has the lowest chance of winning...

774
00:36:34,130 --> 00:36:35,430
among those three. You know that.

775
00:36:35,530 --> 00:36:39,330
And when the type of the game to be played
was announced,

776
00:36:39,630 --> 00:36:43,240
Seung Jin plainly said
he wasn't confident.

777
00:36:43,240 --> 00:36:45,910
The first thing he said was,
"I'm terrible at it."

778
00:36:46,440 --> 00:36:50,680
YunB has his own unique tone
and his own way of moving his head...

779
00:36:50,780 --> 00:36:52,340
when he tries to trick someone.

780
00:36:52,510 --> 00:36:55,310
He moves his head from side to side
like this.

781
00:36:55,810 --> 00:36:59,650
The moment he started his sentence
with "Listen, Jin Hyeong,"

782
00:36:59,750 --> 00:37:04,120
I knew there was no way out.

783
00:37:04,720 --> 00:37:08,330
You can feel a sense of fighting spirit
when you look at a player,

784
00:37:09,090 --> 00:37:11,230
but he doesn't give off
that kind of vibe at all.

785
00:37:11,560 --> 00:37:12,800
Without knowing
what kind of games we'd play,

786
00:37:12,800 --> 00:37:15,570
we came here with the pride
of "Bloody Game 2" on the line.

787
00:37:16,000 --> 00:37:18,570
So I'm not sure if it's right for us
to send the weakest player...

788
00:37:18,570 --> 00:37:20,340
to the Deathmatch.

789
00:37:20,440 --> 00:37:21,970
I feel bad about it, to be honest.

790
00:37:22,680 --> 00:37:24,380
So, what do you want to do?

791
00:37:24,580 --> 00:37:26,380
To be perfectly honest with you,

792
00:37:26,710 --> 00:37:29,680
I hope you can step up
and go to the Deathmatch...

793
00:37:30,050 --> 00:37:33,450
since you have
the most Deathmatch experience among us.

794
00:37:33,450 --> 00:37:35,350
Since Seung Jin volunteered to go,

795
00:37:35,620 --> 00:37:38,490
the matter has been settled peacefully.

796
00:37:38,620 --> 00:37:41,930
But if we want to save all four of us,

797
00:37:42,490 --> 00:37:44,960
you should go
since you have a better chance to survive.

798
00:37:45,230 --> 00:37:48,730
However, you still have to carry a risk,
no matter how small it is.

799
00:37:48,830 --> 00:37:51,540
- Of course, it's bad for you.
- Right.

800
00:37:51,800 --> 00:37:53,740
So we can't force you to volunteer to go.

801
00:37:55,940 --> 00:37:57,440
I thought to myself,
"No one can be trusted, really."

802
00:37:57,440 --> 00:37:59,810
Seeing the two of them
already reach an agreement...

803
00:37:59,910 --> 00:38:01,580
tells me they've made up their minds.

804
00:38:01,580 --> 00:38:02,880
No one can be trusted.

805
00:38:04,450 --> 00:38:06,420
But I know you well.

806
00:38:06,990 --> 00:38:09,960
I know you never want to volunteer to go.

807
00:38:09,960 --> 00:38:12,360
- No one wants to send you there,
- That's right.

808
00:38:12,360 --> 00:38:15,860
- but you have the best chance to survive.
- You have the best chance.

809
00:38:16,160 --> 00:38:19,030
If you think about it,
in the next 3 or 4 days of this game,

810
00:38:19,570 --> 00:38:21,330
you'll eventually make a sacrifice
for the team at least once.

811
00:38:21,500 --> 00:38:23,240
One of us will have to. I'm sure of it.

812
00:38:23,340 --> 00:38:25,800
It'd be cool of you
to be the first to do so.

813
00:38:26,740 --> 00:38:28,240
- You should consider that.
- Gosh, you snakes.

814
00:38:28,240 --> 00:38:31,440
No, we're not trying to trick you.
We're simply being honest with you.

815
00:38:31,740 --> 00:38:34,710
- That's what we're considering...
- I'm going to take a nap.

816
00:38:34,710 --> 00:38:35,950
while planning a strategy.

817
00:38:36,020 --> 00:38:38,520
What I'm saying is that
Seung Jin and I will do this together.

818
00:38:38,520 --> 00:38:40,590
(They continue trying
to convince Jin Hyeong.)

819
00:38:41,020 --> 00:38:42,790
What's going on?
What are you guys talking about?

820
00:38:42,890 --> 00:38:45,520
I think he should hear this too,
if we're going to stick to this plan.

821
00:38:45,760 --> 00:38:48,090
Since they couldn't seem to convince me,

822
00:38:48,290 --> 00:38:50,130
YunB and Sung Joo...

823
00:38:50,400 --> 00:38:52,870
went up to Jin Hyeong
and tried to convince him instead of me.

824
00:38:53,370 --> 00:38:55,470
Imagine how cool it'd be
if you come back after surviving.

825
00:38:55,470 --> 00:38:57,170
I understand what you're trying to say.

826
00:38:57,240 --> 00:38:58,940
- People would think...
- It's more reasonable.

827
00:38:58,940 --> 00:39:01,340
- you've grown into an incredible adult.
- I have a better chance to survive.

828
00:39:01,340 --> 00:39:03,910
If I were in your position
with the abilities you have,

829
00:39:03,980 --> 00:39:04,980
I would definitely go to the Deathmatch.

830
00:39:05,940 --> 00:39:08,510
- Go and crush them all.
- But if you consider the risk...

831
00:39:08,910 --> 00:39:11,580
Losing Jin Hyeong would be a bigger blow
to our team...

832
00:39:11,580 --> 00:39:13,090
than losing me.

833
00:39:13,090 --> 00:39:14,390
- You should think about that.
- That's true as well.

834
00:39:14,390 --> 00:39:16,590
But let's focus on the scenario
where we don't lose anyone...

835
00:39:16,590 --> 00:39:18,190
because that scenario brings us
a bigger advantage.

836
00:39:18,190 --> 00:39:20,230
I stepped up,
and we already settled the matter.

837
00:39:20,230 --> 00:39:21,890
So it seems a bit unfair
to pressure Jin Hyeong...

838
00:39:21,890 --> 00:39:24,730
- into volunteering for the Deathmatch.
- I know. I understand.

839
00:39:24,730 --> 00:39:27,500
I never want to let him go instead of me.

840
00:39:27,500 --> 00:39:29,400
I've made up my mind.

841
00:39:29,670 --> 00:39:31,500
Seung Jin kept saying he'd go.

842
00:39:32,470 --> 00:39:35,570
The game just began.
Who would want to go home now?

843
00:39:35,870 --> 00:39:37,840
Let's just put it to a vote, then.

844
00:39:38,840 --> 00:39:40,610
I won't vote for myself.

845
00:39:40,610 --> 00:39:42,380
I would rather cast a blank ballot.

846
00:39:42,380 --> 00:39:43,680
Voting for myself is...

847
00:39:43,680 --> 00:39:45,380
- completely against my convictions.
- Right.

848
00:39:45,380 --> 00:39:47,150
I would give up my voting right...

849
00:39:47,150 --> 00:39:48,850
- if it comes down to that.
- I understand.

850
00:39:49,320 --> 00:39:52,360
If we fail to convince Seung Jin,
we'll have no choice but to send him.

851
00:40:14,550 --> 00:40:15,580
(Hyun Sung Joo votes for Lee Jin Hyeong.)

852
00:40:18,380 --> 00:40:20,120
(YunB votes for Lee Jin Hyeong.)

853
00:40:21,950 --> 00:40:23,120
Hello.

854
00:40:28,390 --> 00:40:30,800
Please use your team's voting ticket
to vote.

855
00:40:30,930 --> 00:40:31,930
Got it.

856
00:40:33,530 --> 00:40:35,900
(1. Ha Seung Jin, 2. Hyun Sung Joo,
3. YunB, 4. Lee Jin Hyeong)

857
00:40:41,410 --> 00:40:43,210
(Team P2 has finished voting.)

858
00:40:43,210 --> 00:40:44,740
I'm done. Goodbye.

859
00:40:51,580 --> 00:40:54,020
I think there's the highest probability
of that player going to the Deathmatch.

860
00:40:54,820 --> 00:40:58,260
- And as for this team, this player...
- He volunteered to go.

861
00:40:58,260 --> 00:41:00,230
- It's already been settled, apparently.
- This is...

862
00:41:00,230 --> 00:41:02,160
- It's been settled.
- I bet we can beat Seung Jin.

863
00:41:03,430 --> 00:41:04,830
As for this team,

864
00:41:05,500 --> 00:41:08,270
I think
there's a possibility for this one to go.

865
00:41:08,270 --> 00:41:09,400
- Why?
- Why?

866
00:41:09,470 --> 00:41:12,100
The moment one of them suggested
discarding the dead weight,

867
00:41:12,100 --> 00:41:13,410
they entered the Voting Room.

868
00:41:13,510 --> 00:41:15,240
In my opinion,
it can change to this player.

869
00:41:15,640 --> 00:41:18,640
You Hyun said
Team P1 would probably vote...

870
00:41:18,640 --> 00:41:19,710
for the dead weight.

871
00:41:19,710 --> 00:41:22,820
That made me wonder
if our team would do the same thing.

872
00:41:22,880 --> 00:41:25,350
If I have to pick one of us,

873
00:41:25,920 --> 00:41:28,920
I would choose someone
based on what I believe is right.

874
00:41:28,920 --> 00:41:31,090
But I would never force my thoughts
onto the others...

875
00:41:31,090 --> 00:41:34,060
- or tell the others whom I chose.
- Are you saying...

876
00:41:34,060 --> 00:41:35,790
I mean,
this is the result of a team effort.

877
00:41:35,790 --> 00:41:38,200
But you think
we should just put it to a vote...

878
00:41:38,630 --> 00:41:41,800
without any discussion or consensus?
Is that it?

879
00:41:41,900 --> 00:41:42,900
That's right.

880
00:41:43,770 --> 00:41:47,610
I prefer not to share my thoughts
on who should be chosen.

881
00:41:47,810 --> 00:41:49,780
Personally, I do not want to do that.

882
00:41:50,680 --> 00:41:53,250
None of us deserves it.
We all did our best.

883
00:41:53,850 --> 00:41:54,950
- Okay?
- Okay.

884
00:41:56,420 --> 00:41:59,150
Until the very last moment,
You Hyun and Kyoung Hoon...

885
00:41:59,520 --> 00:42:01,050
remained silent about the voting.

886
00:42:01,050 --> 00:42:02,620
The only thing You Hyun said
about the voting was,

887
00:42:02,720 --> 00:42:06,160
"We all just have to vote
for the person of our choice."

888
00:42:06,260 --> 00:42:07,560
In any case,

889
00:42:07,560 --> 00:42:11,760
even though we clearly had a shot
at first place,

890
00:42:11,830 --> 00:42:15,000
we never seemed to go for it.

891
00:42:15,130 --> 00:42:19,200
There are no permanent allies,
and no permanent enemies.

892
00:42:19,940 --> 00:42:21,240
Then why didn't he take the shot?

893
00:42:21,340 --> 00:42:25,580
So I thought our team leader should
take responsibility for our situation.

894
00:42:25,940 --> 00:42:28,480
When we played the game,
they asked if I could handle it...

895
00:42:28,480 --> 00:42:30,350
and stopped me from placing first.

896
00:42:30,580 --> 00:42:33,250
So I thought
they should go to the Deathmatch...

897
00:42:33,250 --> 00:42:35,650
since they stopped me
from winning the game.

898
00:42:36,460 --> 00:42:38,020
I'm really worried.

899
00:42:38,320 --> 00:42:39,990
- Why?
- We have a three-team alliance,

900
00:42:40,090 --> 00:42:42,560
but Team P2 and Team P3 seem
to be closer to each other than to us.

901
00:42:42,830 --> 00:42:45,830
Oh, that alliance?
That doesn't exist anymore.

902
00:42:45,960 --> 00:42:46,970
Was the alliance only meant for today?

903
00:42:46,970 --> 00:42:49,300
- Yes, that's right.
- We can't maintain the alliance...

904
00:42:49,300 --> 00:42:50,640
- ganging up on Team P1.
- That's not fair.

905
00:42:50,640 --> 00:42:52,000
- It's unfair.
- He's right.

906
00:42:52,270 --> 00:42:53,840
- Then...
- It's always a one-day thing.

907
00:42:54,040 --> 00:42:55,770
Really? Then why didn't we betray them?

908
00:42:56,210 --> 00:42:57,410
I find it hard to understand.

909
00:42:57,410 --> 00:42:58,480
- Please explain.
- It doesn't work like that.

910
00:42:58,480 --> 00:42:59,810
We could've betrayed them.

911
00:42:59,910 --> 00:43:03,920
Had we betrayed them,
those two teams would've joined forces...

912
00:43:04,020 --> 00:43:06,020
- and the team...
- We could've allied with Team P1.

913
00:43:06,590 --> 00:43:08,420
Would they have agreed to ally with us?

914
00:43:08,420 --> 00:43:09,620
You don't know that.

915
00:43:09,690 --> 00:43:10,920
- Also, we...
- They would've had no choice.

916
00:43:11,190 --> 00:43:14,290
That's not true. They could've formed
a multi-team alliance with the other two.

917
00:43:14,590 --> 00:43:15,760
That's possible.

918
00:43:15,760 --> 00:43:17,760
- That's why...
- The right time will come again.

919
00:43:18,230 --> 00:43:20,230
There's always a right time
to form an alliance.

920
00:43:20,630 --> 00:43:23,370
We joined forces with Teams P2 and P3
without betraying them,

921
00:43:23,370 --> 00:43:24,670
so I thought the alliance would last.

922
00:43:24,670 --> 00:43:27,740
I thought we took a disadvantage
to preserve the alliance.

923
00:43:28,010 --> 00:43:29,070
But they said it wasn't the case.

924
00:43:29,470 --> 00:43:30,840
They said it was a one-day thing.

925
00:43:30,880 --> 00:43:32,680
Then why didn't we betray them?

926
00:43:32,680 --> 00:43:34,880
Why did they ask me
if I could handle the situation?

927
00:43:37,250 --> 00:43:38,980
We came up with a good strategy.

928
00:43:39,120 --> 00:43:41,520
- Yes.
- I really wanted to stick with it.

929
00:43:41,520 --> 00:43:43,460
- But you saw it...
- Yes.

930
00:43:44,920 --> 00:43:46,760
- You saw me talking to You Hyun...
- Yes.

931
00:43:46,760 --> 00:43:48,330
- by the bed.
- Yes, I did.

932
00:43:48,830 --> 00:43:50,160
- Here's what I think.
- Okay.

933
00:43:50,360 --> 00:43:52,600
If you look at how things turned out
today...

934
00:43:53,800 --> 00:43:56,300
I don't know
what he's talking about over there.

935
00:43:57,040 --> 00:43:59,400
Watching other people whisper
makes you anxious, doesn't it?

936
00:44:00,140 --> 00:44:01,370
- It used to.
- I see.

937
00:44:02,810 --> 00:44:06,410
I thought there was nothing I could do
even if he voted for me.

938
00:44:06,510 --> 00:44:08,010
I mean, Kim Kyoung Hoon is on our team.

939
00:44:08,110 --> 00:44:10,080
Anything can happen.

940
00:44:28,630 --> 00:44:30,540
The voting has ended.

941
00:44:31,040 --> 00:44:33,010
Everyone, please gather in the main hall.

942
00:44:34,310 --> 00:44:36,210
I will announce the results of the vote.

943
00:44:38,740 --> 00:44:41,480
The player from Team P1
heading to the Deathmatch is...

944
00:44:45,950 --> 00:44:49,220
Lee Tae Gyun.

945
00:44:49,890 --> 00:44:52,860
We couldn't send Sang Min
to the Deathmatch this time.

946
00:44:53,330 --> 00:44:56,460
Sang Min is the best on our team
at winning people over...

947
00:44:56,460 --> 00:44:59,030
and dealing with people.

948
00:44:59,030 --> 00:45:00,870
I thought...

949
00:45:00,870 --> 00:45:03,670
that losing him would be a big loss
to our team.

950
00:45:03,840 --> 00:45:07,270
Then who has the best chance
of surviving the Deathmatch?

951
00:45:07,270 --> 00:45:09,810
I think that it would be me.

952
00:45:09,940 --> 00:45:13,280
So... Our final decision is...

953
00:45:13,410 --> 00:45:14,780
that I will be heading to the Deathmatch.

954
00:45:16,050 --> 00:45:17,420
I will make sure to survive.

955
00:45:18,050 --> 00:45:20,590
Tae Gyun desperately wants...

956
00:45:20,590 --> 00:45:22,990
to prove what he can do.

957
00:45:23,190 --> 00:45:25,390
I'm sure that he will win the game
no matter what.

958
00:45:25,790 --> 00:45:27,160
Tae Gyun, make sure to survive.

959
00:45:27,160 --> 00:45:28,290
(1. Lee Sang Min, 2. Jeong Keun Woo,
3. Park Ji Min, 4. Lee Tae Gyun)

960
00:45:31,730 --> 00:45:34,570
I'm going to the Deathmatch
to win the game.

961
00:45:36,600 --> 00:45:38,100
How dare you isolate us?

962
00:45:38,400 --> 00:45:40,410
Fine. I'll meet you in the Deathmatch.

963
00:45:40,510 --> 00:45:43,280
I'll show you what happens when you choose
to play against us in the Deathmatch.

964
00:45:44,310 --> 00:45:47,280
The player from Team P2
heading to the Deathmatch is...

965
00:45:51,750 --> 00:45:54,750
Lee Jin Hyeong.

966
00:45:57,460 --> 00:45:58,790
You're so cool, Jin Hyeong.

967
00:45:59,560 --> 00:46:00,560
What?

968
00:46:00,560 --> 00:46:03,460
Jin Hyeong was chosen? What happened?

969
00:46:03,460 --> 00:46:04,800
Did Seung Jin perhaps beat him up?

970
00:46:05,330 --> 00:46:07,670
It's an unavoidable situation.
There's no escape.

971
00:46:07,970 --> 00:46:09,970
The moment YunB grabbed me...

972
00:46:09,970 --> 00:46:13,570
The moment that snake caught me,
I was doomed.

973
00:46:13,770 --> 00:46:14,910
I had no choice
but to go to the Deathmatch.

974
00:46:15,170 --> 00:46:18,040
I could choose either to march in
on my own feet...

975
00:46:18,210 --> 00:46:21,610
or to be dragged
like a cow to the slaughterhouse.

976
00:46:21,880 --> 00:46:23,680
I had those options.

977
00:46:23,750 --> 00:46:26,220
I'm also worried
I might cause harm to our team.

978
00:46:26,320 --> 00:46:27,550
Then shall I do it?

979
00:46:28,920 --> 00:46:29,920
Don't worry.

980
00:46:30,020 --> 00:46:31,290
They're a bunch of punks.

981
00:46:37,060 --> 00:46:38,930
(1. Ha Seung Jin, 2. Hyun Sung Joo,
3. YunB, 4. Lee Jin Hyeong)

982
00:46:39,130 --> 00:46:40,330
They did hurt my feelings.

983
00:46:40,570 --> 00:46:42,600
They wanted me to go instead of Seung Jin.

984
00:46:42,670 --> 00:46:45,240
But in the end, this is a team game.

985
00:46:45,340 --> 00:46:48,470
And in the long run,
there will be only one winner.

986
00:46:48,640 --> 00:46:49,940
I want to be the winner.

987
00:46:49,940 --> 00:46:52,340
In that sense, I thought...

988
00:46:52,540 --> 00:46:56,010
that volunteering for the Deathmatch
would pay off for me in the long run.

989
00:46:56,010 --> 00:46:57,350
So I'm not very upset.

990
00:46:57,580 --> 00:46:59,380
But I still think they're like snakes.

991
00:47:03,190 --> 00:47:06,220
From Team P1, Lee Tae Gyun,
the winner of Season 1, came out.

992
00:47:06,320 --> 00:47:09,030
And from Team P2, Lee Jin Hyeong,
the winner of Season 2, came out.

993
00:47:09,160 --> 00:47:10,500
I was surprised that
such strong players came out.

994
00:47:11,160 --> 00:47:14,000
The player from Team Challenger
heading to the Deathmatch is...

995
00:47:23,640 --> 00:47:26,510
Kim Nam Hee.

996
00:47:28,810 --> 00:47:31,150
That's crazy. Those guys are losers.

997
00:47:31,350 --> 00:47:32,620
They're losers.

998
00:47:33,220 --> 00:47:34,290
It'll be tough.

999
00:47:41,560 --> 00:47:45,000
(1. Kim Kyoung Hoon, 2. Kim You Hyun,
3. Kim Nam Hee, 4. Kang Ji Hoo)

1000
00:47:48,930 --> 00:47:51,570
(1. Kim Kyoung Hoon, 2. Kim You Hyun,
3. Kim Nam Hee, 4. Kang Ji Hoo)

1001
00:47:54,570 --> 00:47:56,610
(1. Kim Kyoung Hoon, 2. Kim You Hyun,
3. Kim Nam Hee, 4. Kang Ji Hoo)

1002
00:47:58,780 --> 00:48:01,810
You Hyun and Kyoung Hoon are close
to each other,

1003
00:48:02,010 --> 00:48:05,320
so it all came down to
whether they'd vote for Nam Hee or me.

1004
00:48:05,520 --> 00:48:07,790
When the Deathmatch rules are announced,

1005
00:48:07,790 --> 00:48:09,650
we need to pick one elimination candidate
and plan everything around that.

1006
00:48:09,650 --> 00:48:11,420
But if one of us goes to the Deathmatch,

1007
00:48:11,560 --> 00:48:13,560
I don't think
that person will come back to our team.

1008
00:48:13,660 --> 00:48:15,360
I think the player will join another team.

1009
00:48:15,460 --> 00:48:18,760
So I believe that it's most important
for us to figure out...

1010
00:48:18,760 --> 00:48:22,070
which three of us should stay
to maximize the team's strength.

1011
00:48:22,800 --> 00:48:25,740
Rather than losing You Hyun
to another team...

1012
00:48:26,570 --> 00:48:28,570
and having to compete against him...

1013
00:48:28,570 --> 00:48:31,540
and rather than losing you to another team
and having to compete against you,

1014
00:48:32,340 --> 00:48:35,010
I think this would be better.

1015
00:48:35,310 --> 00:48:37,320
Thank you for thinking highly of me.

1016
00:48:38,120 --> 00:48:39,320
The moment we talked about that...

1017
00:48:39,520 --> 00:48:41,320
I mean,
even without mentioning the subject,

1018
00:48:41,320 --> 00:48:42,520
we all know it'd be Nam Hee.

1019
00:48:42,520 --> 00:48:44,390
Everyone was on the same page then.

1020
00:48:44,390 --> 00:48:45,390
So...

1021
00:48:45,520 --> 00:48:48,460
I thought to myself that
Nam Hee had to go this time around.

1022
00:48:48,630 --> 00:48:51,460
Space perception is one of the categories
Mensa tests applicants on, right?

1023
00:48:51,600 --> 00:48:53,630
- We just get geometric figures instead.
- Didn't you get a perfect score?

1024
00:48:53,630 --> 00:48:54,770
We just get geometric figures.

1025
00:48:54,770 --> 00:48:56,070
- Exactly.
- We get geometric puzzles.

1026
00:48:56,200 --> 00:48:57,340
It's not about space perception.

1027
00:48:57,340 --> 00:48:58,770
- It's like if you can drive cars well,
- So basic questions...

1028
00:48:58,770 --> 00:49:00,810
you can drive buses well too. Isn't it?

1029
00:49:01,440 --> 00:49:03,840
They were trying to send me
to the Deathmatch.

1030
00:49:04,210 --> 00:49:06,040
That was the vibe I was getting from them.

1031
00:49:06,980 --> 00:49:10,220
We decided that
we were going to vote however we wanted.

1032
00:49:10,520 --> 00:49:12,780
But I knew they would sacrifice me.

1033
00:49:15,320 --> 00:49:17,890
(Kim Nam Hee votes for Kang Ji Hoo.)

1034
00:49:25,830 --> 00:49:27,070
Thinking back,

1035
00:49:27,530 --> 00:49:30,800
they must have reached
an unspoken agreement like...

1036
00:49:31,100 --> 00:49:32,970
"Will we need her for our future games?"

1037
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:34,870
I'm getting a feeling that
they came to an agreement.

1038
00:49:35,310 --> 00:49:38,510
I need to work harder at the Deathmatch
than the main match.

1039
00:49:40,010 --> 00:49:42,310
Lee Tae Gyun, Lee Jin Hyeong,

1040
00:49:43,010 --> 00:49:44,150
and Kim Nam Hee.

1041
00:49:44,780 --> 00:49:47,920
Leave the mansion
and get ready for the Deathmatch.

1042
00:49:48,320 --> 00:49:49,620
- Good luck.
- Go and win this.

1043
00:49:49,620 --> 00:49:50,620
Let's go.

1044
00:49:51,020 --> 00:49:52,720
- You got this.
- Good luck.

1045
00:49:52,720 --> 00:49:55,190
- Come back.
- You can do this.

1046
00:49:59,600 --> 00:50:01,230
I don't feel good about this.

1047
00:50:02,330 --> 00:50:04,700
She didn't even look back before leaving.

1048
00:50:05,470 --> 00:50:07,570
Of course, she can't feel good about it.

1049
00:50:09,410 --> 00:50:12,140
Players of the Deathmatch,
please gather in the main hall.

1050
00:50:22,750 --> 00:50:24,020
- Good luck.
- Good luck.

1051
00:50:24,990 --> 00:50:26,420
I'm wearing my lucky glasses.

1052
00:50:26,830 --> 00:50:27,990
They make me look smart.

1053
00:50:28,930 --> 00:50:30,230
They must be flustered...

1054
00:50:30,230 --> 00:50:33,700
to find out that their competition is
much stronger than they expected...

1055
00:50:33,700 --> 00:50:35,500
- when they walk in.
- Right.

1056
00:50:35,770 --> 00:50:38,840
At first, I went down there
with pure determination...

1057
00:50:39,040 --> 00:50:41,640
to eliminate those awful people
from isolating us during the game.

1058
00:50:41,870 --> 00:50:44,040
I saw six tables there. So I was like,

1059
00:50:45,080 --> 00:50:48,150
"Three people from outside
are going to join us."

1060
00:50:49,050 --> 00:50:50,580
If only one of us are getting eliminated,

1061
00:50:50,580 --> 00:50:52,450
the three of us didn't have to compete
against each other.

1062
00:50:52,450 --> 00:50:54,150
The three of us could form an alliance...

1063
00:50:54,290 --> 00:50:56,720
and getting 1 of the other 3 players
eliminated would be better.

1064
00:50:56,720 --> 00:51:00,030
We wanted to form a bond
and work together as a team.

1065
00:51:00,030 --> 00:51:01,460
Let's beat them and return victorious.

1066
00:51:01,460 --> 00:51:02,490
Yes.

1067
00:51:02,860 --> 00:51:04,330
- It'd be embarrassing to lose.
- Right.

1068
00:51:04,330 --> 00:51:05,530
- They're rookies.
- Right.

1069
00:51:05,730 --> 00:51:07,030
These rookies came in last too.

1070
00:51:08,570 --> 00:51:11,100
(2 hours ago)

1071
00:51:12,540 --> 00:51:15,140
(An announcement was delivered
to the outdoor survival grounds.)

1072
00:51:15,510 --> 00:51:16,740
Vote...

1073
00:51:16,740 --> 00:51:18,810
- for 1 player who will not participate...
- So the 3 of us will go?

1074
00:51:19,080 --> 00:51:21,450
in the Deathmatch.

1075
00:51:21,780 --> 00:51:23,280
There are four of us.

1076
00:51:23,420 --> 00:51:25,750
The one who stays here
won't be up for elimination.

1077
00:51:26,220 --> 00:51:27,390
That person will survive.

1078
00:51:27,490 --> 00:51:29,820
The best three
should go to the Deathmatch.

1079
00:51:30,090 --> 00:51:32,020
I'm pretty good at that.

1080
00:51:32,420 --> 00:51:35,730
I have good spatial awareness
and quick decision-making abilities.

1081
00:51:35,730 --> 00:51:38,460
I told you from the get-go
that I was confident about this.

1082
00:51:38,700 --> 00:51:42,600
Leaving only one person behind here...

1083
00:51:43,000 --> 00:51:44,300
I didn't expect that.

1084
00:51:44,900 --> 00:51:46,340
Do you think Beom is good at games?

1085
00:51:47,040 --> 00:51:49,840
I'm not sure.
But he sounds very confident.

1086
00:51:50,840 --> 00:51:51,840
Right.

1087
00:51:51,840 --> 00:51:54,980
It worries me that he might not know
much about these survival games.

1088
00:51:55,480 --> 00:51:57,120
I adore him
as the oldest one of our group.

1089
00:51:57,620 --> 00:51:59,080
- But as a player?
- The thing is...

1090
00:51:59,720 --> 00:52:01,450
When judging each other's abilities,

1091
00:52:01,450 --> 00:52:04,190
referring to our achievements was
the easiest to figure out where we stood.

1092
00:52:04,360 --> 00:52:06,690
Yeon Cheong has a high IQ.

1093
00:52:06,690 --> 00:52:08,860
So she must be good at these brain games.

1094
00:52:08,860 --> 00:52:12,100
As for Gwan Hee,
he's been an athlete all his life.

1095
00:52:12,300 --> 00:52:15,130
I thought his spatial awareness
would be better than regular people's.

1096
00:52:15,370 --> 00:52:18,270
I only judged our abilities
based on our careers.

1097
00:52:18,700 --> 00:52:20,240
So I voted for Beom to stay behind.

1098
00:52:20,870 --> 00:52:24,640
Gwan Hee's strategy was to go to
the Deathmatch and come back as winners.

1099
00:52:24,640 --> 00:52:26,540
I liked that, so I agreed.

1100
00:52:26,880 --> 00:52:29,280
I thought I should lead our team.

1101
00:52:29,280 --> 00:52:31,220
If I'm the point guard of our team,

1102
00:52:31,220 --> 00:52:35,220
Yeon Cheong would be the reliable center.

1103
00:52:35,320 --> 00:52:38,090
And Seung Yong would be the sixth man...

1104
00:52:38,090 --> 00:52:39,990
who would be the bridge.

1105
00:52:39,990 --> 00:52:43,330
As for Beom,
he would be a G-league player.

1106
00:52:44,060 --> 00:52:46,330
(Kwak Beom is exempted
from the Deathmatch.)

1107
00:52:46,330 --> 00:52:47,930
My gosh.

1108
00:52:48,370 --> 00:52:49,700
We'll come back as winners.

1109
00:52:51,140 --> 00:52:52,500
- We'll win.
- Yes.

1110
00:52:52,500 --> 00:52:53,740
- We'll come back as winners.
- Okay.

1111
00:52:57,310 --> 00:52:59,110
It made me wonder
if I failed to earn their trust.

1112
00:53:00,080 --> 00:53:01,810
Since they're going to the Deathmatch,

1113
00:53:01,810 --> 00:53:04,350
I want them to do well
and all three of them to come back.

1114
00:53:04,950 --> 00:53:06,520
I believe in your decisions.

1115
00:53:07,190 --> 00:53:09,350
Rookie, Rookie, Rookie, yes.

1116
00:53:11,660 --> 00:53:12,820
This is crazy.

1117
00:53:12,820 --> 00:53:15,290
They've been staying in a mansion.

1118
00:53:16,790 --> 00:53:18,230
- That looks amazing.
- The other four teams...

1119
00:53:18,230 --> 00:53:20,330
couldn't have slept in there
when we were out there, right?

1120
00:53:20,330 --> 00:53:21,770
- I think they did.
- I think they're all there.

1121
00:53:21,770 --> 00:53:23,370
I bet each team got a floor.

1122
00:53:24,370 --> 00:53:25,440
(Surprised)

1123
00:53:25,440 --> 00:53:29,170
So they've been staying
in this amazing mansion.

1124
00:53:29,470 --> 00:53:32,240
I knew that they had some privileges.

1125
00:53:32,240 --> 00:53:36,350
but we were in worlds apart
in terms of our living conditions.

1126
00:53:36,980 --> 00:53:38,220
It was infuriating.

1127
00:53:38,420 --> 00:53:40,550
I didn't want to stay out there anymore.

1128
00:53:40,550 --> 00:53:42,050
I wanted us to win,

1129
00:53:42,050 --> 00:53:44,390
so we could stay in the mansion.
That's what I was thinking.

1130
00:53:44,620 --> 00:53:45,960
We must win no matter what.

1131
00:53:46,690 --> 00:53:47,990
I want to sleep in there too.

1132
00:53:49,130 --> 00:53:50,600
Gosh, we must stay focused.

1133
00:53:50,600 --> 00:53:53,730
We're not here to have fun.
We're not at a vacation home or something.

1134
00:53:54,200 --> 00:53:57,200
- It's not the time to look at the view.
- Are we here to ambush them?

1135
00:53:59,570 --> 00:54:02,810
Players of the Deathmatch,
please enter the main hall.

1136
00:54:05,040 --> 00:54:06,780
- The rookies are here.
- Here come the rookies.

1137
00:54:09,210 --> 00:54:10,420
Hello.

1138
00:54:12,150 --> 00:54:13,220
Hello.

1139
00:54:14,020 --> 00:54:15,020
Hello.

1140
00:54:15,990 --> 00:54:17,120
Good job.

1141
00:54:19,060 --> 00:54:21,390
We thought we'd see three players
from the same team.

1142
00:54:21,830 --> 00:54:24,700
I was like, "Why are there three players
all from different teams?"

1143
00:54:25,200 --> 00:54:26,500
The winner of the first season.

1144
00:54:27,030 --> 00:54:28,370
The winner of the second season.

1145
00:54:29,700 --> 00:54:32,340
I was wondering why
the best players of each team came.

1146
00:54:32,470 --> 00:54:34,870
Coming in last out of six people
rarely happens.

1147
00:54:35,010 --> 00:54:37,910
I thought I wouldn't be going home today.

1148
00:54:40,680 --> 00:54:41,780
Lee Tae Gyun.

1149
00:54:42,510 --> 00:54:43,550
Lee Jin Hyeong.

1150
00:54:44,420 --> 00:54:45,520
Kim Nam Hee.

1151
00:54:46,350 --> 00:54:47,420
Lee Gwan Hee.

1152
00:54:48,220 --> 00:54:49,290
Shin Seung Yong.

1153
00:54:50,190 --> 00:54:51,260
Choi Yeon Cheong.

1154
00:54:52,260 --> 00:54:55,690
The 6 of you must play
a 6-person Deathmatch.

1155
00:54:57,000 --> 00:54:59,030
Here is today's Deathmatch.

1156
00:55:00,230 --> 00:55:01,430
Today's Deathmatch is called...

1157
00:55:02,770 --> 00:55:04,470
(Mosaic Puzzle)

1158
00:55:04,470 --> 00:55:07,010
Mosaic Puzzle.

1159
00:55:08,070 --> 00:55:10,480
In this puzzle game,
your goal is to score high...

1160
00:55:10,480 --> 00:55:12,640
by arranging the tiles to create...

1161
00:55:12,640 --> 00:55:14,980
the largest possible chains
of the same color.

1162
00:55:16,150 --> 00:55:19,050
Each player will receive...

1163
00:55:19,250 --> 00:55:21,320
a 16-square game board...

1164
00:55:21,320 --> 00:55:23,590
consisting of 4 rows and 4 columns.

1165
00:55:24,120 --> 00:55:26,560
Once the game begins,
a total of 90 color tiles,

1166
00:55:26,560 --> 00:55:28,460
each featuring four colors...

1167
00:55:28,460 --> 00:55:31,130
randomly arranged in four quadrants.

1168
00:55:32,260 --> 00:55:33,870
Starting with the first player,

1169
00:55:33,870 --> 00:55:36,000
each player will take turns
to pick 1 of the 3 color tiles...

1170
00:55:36,170 --> 00:55:38,040
in front of the pawn.

1171
00:55:39,040 --> 00:55:41,270
Once the player takes the tile,

1172
00:55:41,610 --> 00:55:44,180
the pawn will move to the location
of the chosen tile.

1173
00:55:44,480 --> 00:55:46,640
The next player must take
1 of the 3 color tiles...

1174
00:55:46,640 --> 00:55:48,410
in front of the pawn.

1175
00:55:49,580 --> 00:55:53,220
This process will continue to obtain tiles
until the players...

1176
00:55:53,650 --> 00:55:55,690
run out of the 90 color tiles.

1177
00:55:56,450 --> 00:55:58,090
The tiles the players obtain...

1178
00:55:58,490 --> 00:56:01,530
can go to any boxes on their game board.

1179
00:56:01,990 --> 00:56:05,160
Before putting it down,
they can freely rotate the tiles.

1180
00:56:05,960 --> 00:56:07,930
However, once the tiles are on the board,

1181
00:56:07,930 --> 00:56:10,640
they can be neither moved nor rotated.

1182
00:56:11,270 --> 00:56:13,000
To bring a new tile,

1183
00:56:13,200 --> 00:56:15,640
they must put down the tile on the board.

1184
00:56:16,570 --> 00:56:19,010
Once all the players have 15 tiles...

1185
00:56:19,180 --> 00:56:21,510
on their game board,

1186
00:56:21,510 --> 00:56:24,150
they will have to 30 minutes
to rearrange the tiles.

1187
00:56:24,380 --> 00:56:26,650
The players aren't allowed to communicate.

1188
00:56:27,820 --> 00:56:30,320
During this time,
they can push the tiles...

1189
00:56:30,320 --> 00:56:31,860
to an empty box.

1190
00:56:32,290 --> 00:56:34,660
But they can't rotate the tiles.

1191
00:56:35,660 --> 00:56:37,300
During this time,

1192
00:56:37,300 --> 00:56:41,300
the players can register their score
whenever they want.

1193
00:56:42,500 --> 00:56:45,470
Here's how the points will be calculated.

1194
00:56:45,870 --> 00:56:47,670
For each color,

1195
00:56:47,870 --> 00:56:50,710
the score is determined
by the largest number...

1196
00:56:50,810 --> 00:56:52,340
of connected squares of that color.

1197
00:56:52,340 --> 00:56:53,510
(7 points, 4 points, 7 points,
and 3 points)

1198
00:56:53,510 --> 00:56:56,680
And the sum of the two highest colors...

1199
00:56:56,850 --> 00:56:58,380
will be the player's score.

1200
00:56:58,850 --> 00:57:01,590
The lowest of registered scores...

1201
00:57:02,090 --> 00:57:05,160
will be revealed simultaneously
in the main hall.

1202
00:57:05,620 --> 00:57:07,330
Five minutes before the game ends,

1203
00:57:07,530 --> 00:57:09,730
the lowest score won't be revealed.

1204
00:57:10,330 --> 00:57:12,430
Once the time to rearrange the tiles
is over,

1205
00:57:12,660 --> 00:57:14,770
the highest of registered scores...

1206
00:57:14,770 --> 00:57:18,340
by each player will be their final score.

1207
00:57:18,570 --> 00:57:21,070
The player with the lowest final score...

1208
00:57:21,470 --> 00:57:23,310
will be eliminated.

1209
00:57:23,470 --> 00:57:26,240
If the lowest score is tied
by two or more players,

1210
00:57:26,410 --> 00:57:27,850
the points from the other two colors...

1211
00:57:27,850 --> 00:57:30,010
which weren't added to the sum
will be combined to the score.

1212
00:57:30,280 --> 00:57:33,520
The player with the lower score then
will be eliminated.

1213
00:57:34,490 --> 00:57:37,560
Mosaic Puzzle will begin shortly.

1214
00:57:39,560 --> 00:57:42,760
When the puzzle game was announced,

1215
00:57:43,030 --> 00:57:45,130
I knew I would be good at this.

1216
00:57:45,260 --> 00:57:46,660
Luck played an important part.

1217
00:57:46,900 --> 00:57:49,200
But arrangement would be crucial
in this game.

1218
00:57:49,700 --> 00:57:51,600
I focused on not making any mistakes...

1219
00:57:51,600 --> 00:57:53,470
and not rotating the tiles.

1220
00:57:53,600 --> 00:57:56,470
The game board consisted of 16 boxes.

1221
00:57:56,810 --> 00:58:00,510
But we'll only use 15 boxes out of 16.

1222
00:58:00,750 --> 00:58:03,280
I thought about how many points
I needed to be safe.

1223
00:58:03,550 --> 00:58:05,850
Let's say I obtain 2 points with 1 block.

1224
00:58:05,920 --> 00:58:08,520
I'd get 30 points.
That would be a very high score.

1225
00:58:08,950 --> 00:58:12,490
Probability-wise,
scoring over 25 points...

1226
00:58:12,760 --> 00:58:14,260
would definitely be safe.

1227
00:58:15,260 --> 00:58:17,560
You'll draw cards to decide the order.

1228
00:58:17,960 --> 00:58:20,130
Lee Tae Gyun, please draw a card.

1229
00:58:21,800 --> 00:58:24,170
Lee Tae Gyun drew number six.

1230
00:58:24,300 --> 00:58:26,770
Lee Jin Hyeong drew number five.

1231
00:58:27,070 --> 00:58:29,540
Kim Nam Hee drew number two.

1232
00:58:30,680 --> 00:58:32,940
Lee Gwan Hee drew number four.

1233
00:58:33,210 --> 00:58:35,380
Shin Seung Yong drew number three.

1234
00:58:35,810 --> 00:58:38,220
Choi Yeon Cheong drew number one.

1235
00:58:38,720 --> 00:58:40,890
(The order of players: Choi Yeon Cheong,
Kim Nam Hee, Shin Seung Yong,)

1236
00:58:40,890 --> 00:58:42,750
(Lee Gwan Hee, Lee Jin Hyeong,
Lee Tae Gyun)

1237
00:58:42,990 --> 00:58:45,260
You will now obtain the tiles.

1238
00:58:45,590 --> 00:58:47,860
Choi Yeon Cheong, please pick a tile.

1239
00:58:52,400 --> 00:58:53,530
She must feel uncomfortable.

1240
00:58:56,730 --> 00:58:59,840
(She can choose from these three cards.)

1241
00:59:01,240 --> 00:59:05,080
(Choi Yeon Cheong picks the first tile.)

1242
00:59:05,080 --> 00:59:07,250
Kim Nam Hee, please pick a tile.

1243
00:59:11,720 --> 00:59:14,020
(Nam Hee picks the third tile.)

1244
00:59:14,350 --> 00:59:16,220
I didn't get it.

1245
00:59:16,920 --> 00:59:19,490
Having a tile with two boxes
of the same color was very important.

1246
00:59:19,560 --> 00:59:21,490
We need a tile with two box
of the same color...

1247
00:59:21,490 --> 00:59:23,690
in order to continue
the chain of the same color.

1248
00:59:24,330 --> 00:59:27,430
If Nam Hee took the first tile,

1249
00:59:28,170 --> 00:59:31,970
the next player, Seung Yong,
would have had unfavorable tiles.

1250
00:59:33,040 --> 00:59:34,870
However, Nam Hee...

1251
00:59:35,140 --> 00:59:38,480
went after Yeon Cheong
who just took a yellow tile.

1252
00:59:38,980 --> 00:59:42,680
Collecting yellow tiles
wouldn't have been wise.

1253
00:59:43,510 --> 00:59:45,980
Just like this, in Mosaic Puzzle,

1254
00:59:46,250 --> 00:59:48,250
depending on which tile players take,

1255
00:59:48,450 --> 00:59:51,190
they can complicate the game
for the next player.

1256
00:59:52,020 --> 00:59:54,190
Lee Jin Hyeong, please pick a tile.

1257
00:59:55,190 --> 00:59:56,990
Yeon Cheong took yellow.
Seung Yong took red.

1258
00:59:57,560 --> 00:59:58,700
Gwan Hee took blue.

1259
00:59:59,160 --> 01:00:00,770
You should take yellow.
And I should take red.

1260
01:00:01,670 --> 01:00:03,100
Out of the tiles I could take,

1261
01:00:03,100 --> 01:00:05,040
the tile with two boxes of the same color
was yellow.

1262
01:00:05,040 --> 01:00:07,170
I wasn't happy that
Yeon Cheong and I overlapped in color.

1263
01:00:07,340 --> 01:00:10,010
But I thought getting a tile with
two boxes of the same color would be wise.

1264
01:00:10,010 --> 01:00:12,380
- So I took the yellow tile.
- It'd change things.

1265
01:00:16,010 --> 01:00:17,780
I should keep the green box
open like this, right?

1266
01:00:18,480 --> 01:00:19,520
Like this?

1267
01:00:19,820 --> 01:00:21,890
Actually, when you pick a tile
with two boxes of the same color,

1268
01:00:22,520 --> 01:00:23,990
you must place it in the center.

1269
01:00:24,360 --> 01:00:27,990
The moment you let the two boxes
touch the edge of the board,

1270
01:00:28,130 --> 01:00:30,290
you wouldn't be able to connect them
from those sides. But...

1271
01:00:30,760 --> 01:00:32,760
I should keep the green box
open like this, right?

1272
01:00:32,900 --> 01:00:36,470
But Jin Hyeong thought for a long time
about where to place...

1273
01:00:36,570 --> 01:00:39,300
his first tile on his board.

1274
01:00:40,470 --> 01:00:41,810
- You can push it later.
- Yes.

1275
01:00:41,810 --> 01:00:43,210
It's the same thing, actually.

1276
01:00:44,210 --> 01:00:45,280
The truth is,

1277
01:00:45,680 --> 01:00:47,780
I knew this trick, but I didn't tell him.

1278
01:00:48,480 --> 01:00:51,050
The moment Jin Hyeong put down the tile
in the corner,

1279
01:00:51,150 --> 01:00:52,920
I had zero chance of getting eliminated.

1280
01:00:53,120 --> 01:00:55,190
Here's the thing.

1281
01:00:55,550 --> 01:00:58,320
This Deathmatch looked like
it was a 3-on-3 game.

1282
01:00:58,860 --> 01:01:01,130
But my priority was my survival.

1283
01:01:01,560 --> 01:01:03,890
Lee Tae Gyun, please pick a tile.

1284
01:01:04,460 --> 01:01:06,960
- You didn't take green, right?
- Right. Green or blue.

1285
01:01:06,960 --> 01:01:08,000
(He picks the tile with two red boxes.)

1286
01:01:08,000 --> 01:01:09,000
Blue...

1287
01:01:09,000 --> 01:01:10,500
(Tile Arrangement of Round 1)

1288
01:01:10,500 --> 01:01:13,140
(Tile Arrangement of Round 2)

1289
01:01:13,540 --> 01:01:15,670
Choi Yeon Cheong, please pick a tile.

1290
01:01:15,670 --> 01:01:17,610
(Yeon Cheong is collecting yellow tiles.)

1291
01:01:17,610 --> 01:01:19,010
During my third turn,

1292
01:01:19,380 --> 01:01:22,380
there was a tile I was eyeing.

1293
01:01:23,380 --> 01:01:24,720
But Jin Hyeong took it.

1294
01:01:25,480 --> 01:01:28,050
Her main color is yellow, and so is mine.

1295
01:01:28,250 --> 01:01:30,660
So obtaining a lot of yellow cards
would be a way...

1296
01:01:30,660 --> 01:01:32,490
to put pressure on her.

1297
01:01:32,760 --> 01:01:35,430
I kept trying to make things difficult
for Yeon Cheong.

1298
01:01:39,900 --> 01:01:42,000
(She's forced to take another tile.)

1299
01:01:42,270 --> 01:01:44,570
Lee Jin Hyeong, please pick a tile.

1300
01:01:45,500 --> 01:01:48,240
I had to connect the yellow tiles,
so I took a tile with one yellow box.

1301
01:01:48,610 --> 01:01:52,010
After that, I was struggling to figure out
where to place the tile.

1302
01:01:54,750 --> 01:01:55,810
What?

1303
01:01:56,410 --> 01:01:58,020
Then I only get two points for red.

1304
01:01:58,150 --> 01:01:59,150
- What?
- So...

1305
01:01:59,150 --> 01:02:00,580
with this, I only have two points for red.

1306
01:02:01,290 --> 01:02:03,450
So you want me to focus on yellow?

1307
01:02:05,420 --> 01:02:06,620
Don't look at my mess.

1308
01:02:08,290 --> 01:02:09,530
I thought I smelled something nasty.

1309
01:02:09,530 --> 01:02:11,460
- This is embarrassing.
- I'm joking.

1310
01:02:12,930 --> 01:02:13,930
Okay.

1311
01:02:13,930 --> 01:02:17,640
Or you can try to bring out
the yellow tiles this way.

1312
01:02:17,900 --> 01:02:19,800
- You should save the red chain.
- I should save the red chain.

1313
01:02:20,740 --> 01:02:22,370
I think Tae Gyun is smarter than me.

1314
01:02:22,570 --> 01:02:23,970
He's better than me.

1315
01:02:24,940 --> 01:02:26,780
(Tile Arrangement of Round 3)

1316
01:02:26,780 --> 01:02:29,110
(Tile Arrangement of Round 4)

1317
01:02:29,280 --> 01:02:30,280
Shin Seung Yong,

1318
01:02:30,280 --> 01:02:31,820
- please pick a tile.
- Which one will you take?

1319
01:02:32,780 --> 01:02:34,320
I should pick the green one.

1320
01:02:34,320 --> 01:02:36,290
- It's the same.
- I can stop them from taking this.

1321
01:02:36,290 --> 01:02:38,390
You want to take the two blue boxes,
right?

1322
01:02:38,390 --> 01:02:41,630
Back then, my choice was limited.

1323
01:02:41,830 --> 01:02:45,900
Taking the tile with two yellow boxes
was the best choice.

1324
01:02:46,000 --> 01:02:49,330
After Gwan Hee, it was Jin Hyeong's turn.

1325
01:02:49,630 --> 01:02:51,370
If I took that one,

1326
01:02:51,370 --> 01:02:53,500
Jin Hyeong would be able to take a tile
with two green boxes.

1327
01:02:53,500 --> 01:02:54,540
So...

1328
01:02:54,640 --> 01:02:57,580
I decided to change my sub color to green.

1329
01:02:57,580 --> 01:02:59,940
I thought it was the second-best choice.

1330
01:03:00,110 --> 01:03:02,110
So I decided to change my sub color.

1331
01:03:02,810 --> 01:03:03,980
(He picks the green tile...)

1332
01:03:03,980 --> 01:03:07,890
(to prevent Jin Hyeong
from taking the green tile.)

1333
01:03:10,050 --> 01:03:11,620
Jin Hyeong had the biggest disadvantage.

1334
01:03:11,990 --> 01:03:14,660
If only one of our opponents
had been between us,

1335
01:03:14,890 --> 01:03:16,190
helping each other would've been easy.

1336
01:03:16,260 --> 01:03:18,960
But if two opponents were between us,

1337
01:03:19,130 --> 01:03:21,600
based on the number of moves they made,

1338
01:03:21,770 --> 01:03:24,970
it would determine
what tiles they could or couldn't obtain.

1339
01:03:25,170 --> 01:03:27,000
So Jin Hyeong was at a disadvantage.

1340
01:03:28,910 --> 01:03:30,810
Lee Jin Hyeong, please pick a tile.

1341
01:03:30,810 --> 01:03:31,880
- Let's see.
- Okay.

1342
01:03:32,010 --> 01:03:33,780
You can't connect the blue boxes.

1343
01:03:33,910 --> 01:03:35,380
- I don't have any blue boxes.
- I see.

1344
01:03:35,980 --> 01:03:37,450
This is really hard.

1345
01:03:37,820 --> 01:03:39,680
Should you go with red and green instead?

1346
01:03:40,420 --> 01:03:41,450
- Red and green?
- He must go with green.

1347
01:03:41,450 --> 01:03:43,020
- But...
- It's pointless, though.

1348
01:03:43,020 --> 01:03:44,460
One of these two will get blocked.

1349
01:03:44,460 --> 01:03:46,060
- One of them will be discarded.
- I can keep only one of them.

1350
01:03:46,190 --> 01:03:47,360
To make it worse,

1351
01:03:47,360 --> 01:03:49,230
Jin Hyeong's tile arrangement
wasn't the best.

1352
01:03:49,290 --> 01:03:51,860
He had no choice
but to push his tiles later.

1353
01:03:52,360 --> 01:03:53,460
- If you put that down,
- Red?

1354
01:03:53,460 --> 01:03:54,500
you'll break everything up.

1355
01:03:54,930 --> 01:03:56,070
You won't be able to rearrange them.

1356
01:03:56,400 --> 01:03:57,430
Right.

1357
01:03:57,430 --> 01:03:58,570
You made a mistake with the first one.

1358
01:03:58,570 --> 01:04:00,340
Exactly. I messed up there.

1359
01:04:01,170 --> 01:04:02,810
I messed up big time.

1360
01:04:03,510 --> 01:04:04,540
Gosh, this is embarrassing.

1361
01:04:04,540 --> 01:04:05,610
(Tile Arrangement of Round 5)

1362
01:04:05,610 --> 01:04:07,340
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1363
01:04:08,880 --> 01:04:10,280
- This isn't easy.
- You don't have that.

1364
01:04:15,750 --> 01:04:16,790
(Sighing)

1365
01:04:16,790 --> 01:04:17,960
My life is doomed.

1366
01:04:18,360 --> 01:04:20,120
I started to get anxious then.

1367
01:04:20,320 --> 01:04:24,160
I planned my arrangement
expecting to get certain tiles.

1368
01:04:24,400 --> 01:04:26,700
But those tiles wouldn't just show up.

1369
01:04:26,700 --> 01:04:27,700
Even if I was close to those tiles,

1370
01:04:27,700 --> 01:04:31,040
Seung Yong and Gwan Hee
kept taking the tiles.

1371
01:04:31,140 --> 01:04:33,340
Afterward, I started to get very anxious.

1372
01:04:35,340 --> 01:04:36,570
- By the way,
- Yes.

1373
01:04:38,210 --> 01:04:41,480
at this point, we could use the tactic
to target the lowest-scoring player...

1374
01:04:41,480 --> 01:04:43,780
- to solidify the outcome.
- Right.

1375
01:04:43,780 --> 01:04:45,620
We have the best chance to do that
with Seung Yong.

1376
01:04:45,620 --> 01:04:46,850
- Right.
- Yes.

1377
01:04:47,620 --> 01:04:48,690
(Flinching)

1378
01:04:48,690 --> 01:04:49,690
Did you hear that?

1379
01:04:49,690 --> 01:04:51,360
- It was obvious you were plotting.
- Did you hear everything?

1380
01:04:51,390 --> 01:04:52,760
We play dirty.

1381
01:04:53,820 --> 01:04:54,960
Okay.

1382
01:04:55,130 --> 01:04:56,930
There's a high chance that
Seung Yong would end up last.

1383
01:04:56,930 --> 01:04:59,500
But look at Gwan Hee's board.
He just has a lot of blue boxes.

1384
01:04:59,500 --> 01:05:00,700
- He's got no sub color.
- Right.

1385
01:05:00,800 --> 01:05:02,130
- He has a low score too.
- I think...

1386
01:05:02,130 --> 01:05:03,370
- We can keep collecting blue.
- Right.

1387
01:05:03,370 --> 01:05:04,470
- Yes.
- Right.

1388
01:05:04,470 --> 01:05:06,770
We need to make it difficult for them.

1389
01:05:07,570 --> 01:05:09,270
Some of them go one after another.

1390
01:05:10,510 --> 01:05:12,580
I'm sorry.
There are no hard feelings, right?

1391
01:05:12,980 --> 01:05:14,380
- It's fine.
- Okay.

1392
01:05:15,180 --> 01:05:17,580
- You made it difficult for us too.
- We've never met before.

1393
01:05:17,580 --> 01:05:18,750
- That's a given.
- Yes.

1394
01:05:18,880 --> 01:05:21,690
I thought Seung Yong and Gwan Hee had...

1395
01:05:21,950 --> 01:05:23,850
a bit of a disadvantage.

1396
01:05:23,920 --> 01:05:26,320
I thought they weren't doing so well
with the game.

1397
01:05:26,320 --> 01:05:28,730
So I gently let them know...

1398
01:05:28,730 --> 01:05:31,530
that they were my targets.

1399
01:05:31,760 --> 01:05:33,760
- We can do that.
- But you guys shouldn't get too close...

1400
01:05:33,860 --> 01:05:37,100
because I picked one of you as my target.

1401
01:05:37,300 --> 01:05:39,270
- Darn it.
- Suit yourself.

1402
01:05:39,270 --> 01:05:41,470
- That's scary.
- I don't care.

1403
01:05:44,380 --> 01:05:47,180
Yeon Cheong. Actually,

1404
01:05:47,950 --> 01:05:49,910
you're on top.

1405
01:05:50,180 --> 01:05:52,150
So there's no need
to make enemies out of us.

1406
01:05:52,480 --> 01:05:54,150
Only one of us will get eliminated.

1407
01:05:54,150 --> 01:05:55,150
No.

1408
01:05:55,150 --> 01:05:58,560
Listen. We only have one target anyway.

1409
01:05:58,560 --> 01:05:59,860
We'll take care of it ourselves.

1410
01:05:59,860 --> 01:06:01,230
- You don't need to...
- Listen.

1411
01:06:01,230 --> 01:06:02,990
- You don't have to worry about us.
- It's not that.

1412
01:06:02,990 --> 01:06:05,330
- We're trying... No. If you survive...
- You're our target.

1413
01:06:05,330 --> 01:06:06,660
We don't need you to intervene.

1414
01:06:06,700 --> 01:06:08,970
- You should team up with the majority.
- Don't talk to my team.

1415
01:06:08,970 --> 01:06:10,170
Don't talk to my team.

1416
01:06:10,170 --> 01:06:13,100
The five of us should be on the same team.

1417
01:06:13,900 --> 01:06:15,040
Think carefully.

1418
01:06:15,210 --> 01:06:16,810
You don't know
which five will end up on that team.

1419
01:06:16,810 --> 01:06:17,980
The five of us here.

1420
01:06:17,980 --> 01:06:19,440
- Which five?
- I don't know.

1421
01:06:19,440 --> 01:06:20,680
- But...
- These are her evil whispers.

1422
01:06:21,150 --> 01:06:23,310
Don't listen to her evil whispers.
We're on the same team.

1423
01:06:24,080 --> 01:06:25,620
You don't need to provoke them.

1424
01:06:25,620 --> 01:06:26,720
- It's fine.
- Okay.

1425
01:06:27,750 --> 01:06:29,350
It was really infuriating.

1426
01:06:29,990 --> 01:06:31,560
I've never played with...

1427
01:06:31,560 --> 01:06:34,460
someone so ill-mannered and infuriating.

1428
01:06:34,630 --> 01:06:37,360
It wasn't just that.
She dropped the honorifics to us.

1429
01:06:37,730 --> 01:06:39,060
Sure, I can understand trash talk.

1430
01:06:39,060 --> 01:06:41,670
If it's part of the game,

1431
01:06:41,670 --> 01:06:45,040
I can put up with it.

1432
01:06:45,270 --> 01:06:47,240
But what she did wasn't part of the game.

1433
01:06:47,970 --> 01:06:51,740
I think it was a matter
of respect and manners.

1434
01:06:51,940 --> 01:06:53,410
She definitely ruined my vibe.

1435
01:06:54,880 --> 01:06:55,910
(Tile Arrangement of Round 6)

1436
01:06:55,910 --> 01:06:57,780
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1437
01:06:58,080 --> 01:06:59,620
We need to take nine more tiles.

1438
01:06:59,620 --> 01:07:01,120
- We have a long way to go.
- Yes, we do.

1439
01:07:01,820 --> 01:07:03,650
No, this isn't good. It's blocked here.

1440
01:07:03,650 --> 01:07:05,520
- The red... There are no more red tiles.
- It's blocked.

1441
01:07:05,520 --> 01:07:08,390
- No more. Actually, I think...
- This...

1442
01:07:08,790 --> 01:07:09,860
It's blocked.

1443
01:07:10,390 --> 01:07:14,230
(Staring)

1444
01:07:14,230 --> 01:07:15,400
- We can go with this here.
- Okay.

1445
01:07:15,400 --> 01:07:16,870
It's better to use it here.

1446
01:07:16,870 --> 01:07:18,200
- Push it to the side.
- Yes.

1447
01:07:18,200 --> 01:07:19,570
- If I do that, I'll be ruined.
- The space...

1448
01:07:19,570 --> 01:07:21,170
- They won't be connected.
- Why?

1449
01:07:21,340 --> 01:07:22,370
- Around here...
- Yes.

1450
01:07:22,710 --> 01:07:24,010
- I must be having fun.
- Wait.

1451
01:07:24,010 --> 01:07:25,110
- I'll do that then.
- Okay.

1452
01:07:25,580 --> 01:07:27,680
If we do that, we can totally...

1453
01:07:27,850 --> 01:07:29,780
- Excuse me.
- "Excuse me?"

1454
01:07:30,480 --> 01:07:33,080
- Yeon Cheong's yellow chain is over.
- Yes?

1455
01:07:33,080 --> 01:07:34,950
- Do you want to see it? It's over.
- What?

1456
01:07:35,090 --> 01:07:37,550
Look at her board.
If she doesn't get any yellow tiles...

1457
01:07:37,550 --> 01:07:39,220
- Without that...
- She can't expand it.

1458
01:07:39,220 --> 01:07:41,160
- Yes. Things will get embarrassing.
- Okay.

1459
01:07:41,160 --> 01:07:42,990
- She doesn't have a sub color.
- Right. They're all the same.

1460
01:07:43,730 --> 01:07:47,360
We were able to see the others' boards.

1461
01:07:47,900 --> 01:07:49,870
We could sort of calculate their scores.

1462
01:07:50,070 --> 01:07:51,500
Seung Yong, Yeon Cheong,

1463
01:07:51,500 --> 01:07:53,400
and Jin Hyeong were in the same boat.

1464
01:07:53,400 --> 01:07:56,110
But Seung Yong placed his tiles
strategically,

1465
01:07:56,170 --> 01:07:58,410
so he was in a better position
to expand his colors.

1466
01:07:58,510 --> 01:08:01,150
As for Yeon Cheong, she didn't do
a good job with the arrangement.

1467
01:08:01,150 --> 01:08:02,950
She had very little choice
about expanding her colors.

1468
01:08:03,410 --> 01:08:06,820
From now on, our first priority is...

1469
01:08:06,980 --> 01:08:08,720
to take green and blue tiles.

1470
01:08:08,850 --> 01:08:10,150
The second priority is...

1471
01:08:10,490 --> 01:08:13,190
that if we can help him get yellow tiles,
we must help him...

1472
01:08:13,190 --> 01:08:14,190
- no matter what.
- Right.

1473
01:08:14,190 --> 01:08:16,530
And I can fill up my board
while taking away green.

1474
01:08:16,530 --> 01:08:17,730
- Let's take green tiles...
- Yes.

1475
01:08:17,730 --> 01:08:18,930
- while helping me get tiles.
- Okay.

1476
01:08:18,930 --> 01:08:21,230
- We should take green and then yellow.
- Okay.

1477
01:08:21,230 --> 01:08:22,300
(Tile Arrangement of Round 7)

1478
01:08:22,300 --> 01:08:23,900
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1479
01:08:23,900 --> 01:08:24,970
(Tile Arrangement of Round 8)

1480
01:08:24,970 --> 01:08:26,840
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1481
01:08:26,840 --> 01:08:28,610
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1482
01:08:29,010 --> 01:08:31,140
Choi Yeon Cheong, please pick a tile.

1483
01:08:41,120 --> 01:08:43,720
I saw my limit for yellow
with 12 being the highest.

1484
01:08:44,820 --> 01:08:47,190
So I needed to score over seven
with green.

1485
01:08:47,360 --> 01:08:49,190
And I thought the player in last place...

1486
01:08:49,460 --> 01:08:51,630
shouldn't rotate the tiles.

1487
01:08:53,130 --> 01:08:54,130
Lee Jin Hyeong,

1488
01:08:54,130 --> 01:08:55,700
- please pick a tile.
- Let's go and get it.

1489
01:08:55,970 --> 01:08:57,000
I need a yellow tile here.

1490
01:08:57,000 --> 01:08:58,370
- So I could expand one more tile.
- Yes.

1491
01:08:58,370 --> 01:09:00,140
But I don't have any tiles
with yellow and green.

1492
01:09:00,340 --> 01:09:01,640
- No, there is.
- No. There is one.

1493
01:09:01,640 --> 01:09:02,840
- Should I take that?
- Yes, take that.

1494
01:09:02,840 --> 01:09:03,910
- I'll take it then.
- Yes.

1495
01:09:06,140 --> 01:09:09,380
(It's imperative for Jin Hyeong
to obtain green and yellow tiles.)

1496
01:09:09,380 --> 01:09:10,480
(Tile Arrangement of Round 9)

1497
01:09:10,480 --> 01:09:12,350
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1498
01:09:12,350 --> 01:09:14,120
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1499
01:09:15,550 --> 01:09:16,590
What about me?

1500
01:09:17,450 --> 01:09:19,520
Two, four, six, eight, ten.

1501
01:09:19,660 --> 01:09:20,760
Eleven.

1502
01:09:21,660 --> 01:09:23,060
Seventeen. Eighteen.

1503
01:09:23,690 --> 01:09:25,160
I have eighteen points so far.

1504
01:09:26,000 --> 01:09:27,630
I was able to collect...

1505
01:09:27,630 --> 01:09:30,130
red and blue tiles
without any disconnection.

1506
01:09:30,130 --> 01:09:33,800
So there was no chance
that I would get eliminated.

1507
01:09:33,900 --> 01:09:35,040
After that point,

1508
01:09:35,040 --> 01:09:37,640
I was more focused
on helping Nam Hee and Jin Hyeong.

1509
01:09:37,880 --> 01:09:39,740
- Jin Hyeong. Bring this down.
- Yes.

1510
01:09:39,740 --> 01:09:40,910
So this goes here.

1511
01:09:41,180 --> 01:09:43,550
Bring these tiles down here.

1512
01:09:43,550 --> 01:09:45,020
- Like this.
- Okay.

1513
01:09:45,220 --> 01:09:47,180
So if you push these tiles...

1514
01:09:47,180 --> 01:09:49,190
and bring this up, it works.

1515
01:09:49,350 --> 01:09:51,490
One, two, three, four, five, six,
seven, eight, nine, ten,

1516
01:09:51,490 --> 01:09:53,020
eleven, twelve, and thirteen.
You got thirteen.

1517
01:09:53,160 --> 01:09:56,490
First of all,
Yeon Cheong and Seung Yong...

1518
01:09:56,490 --> 01:09:59,700
I helped them obtain more blue tiles.

1519
01:09:59,800 --> 01:10:01,230
I didn't focus on scoring for myself.

1520
01:10:01,230 --> 01:10:03,000
I helped Yeon Cheong obtain...

1521
01:10:03,000 --> 01:10:04,400
more tiles as if it were mine.

1522
01:10:04,700 --> 01:10:06,740
With thirteen, if you can score...

1523
01:10:06,740 --> 01:10:08,710
five points with red or green,

1524
01:10:09,410 --> 01:10:11,440
- you'll beat Jin Hyeong for sure.
- How many does he have?

1525
01:10:11,440 --> 01:10:12,440
Fourteen or fifteen.

1526
01:10:12,440 --> 01:10:14,650
- The second one.
- Choi Yeon Cheong, please pick a tile.

1527
01:10:14,980 --> 01:10:16,050
(Tile Arrangement of Round 10)

1528
01:10:16,050 --> 01:10:18,480
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1529
01:10:18,920 --> 01:10:20,650
- Let's see.
- Take this.

1530
01:10:20,720 --> 01:10:27,690
(Gwan Hee studies
Jin Hyeong's board closely.)

1531
01:10:27,690 --> 01:10:28,960
You need green, right?

1532
01:10:29,260 --> 01:10:30,460
- Both...
- Both colors work for me.

1533
01:10:30,460 --> 01:10:32,230
- Green...
- Yellow works for me too.

1534
01:10:35,370 --> 01:10:37,100
It's Choi Yeon Cheong's turn.

1535
01:10:37,600 --> 01:10:38,740
Take that.

1536
01:10:39,900 --> 01:10:41,040
She took green.

1537
01:10:43,140 --> 01:10:45,280
(Sighing)

1538
01:10:45,280 --> 01:10:46,780
- It's Nam Hee's turn.
- Nam Hee.

1539
01:10:47,510 --> 01:10:48,550
That's it.

1540
01:10:49,580 --> 01:10:50,810
I'll go and place my tile down.

1541
01:10:52,150 --> 01:10:53,920
- If she takes green...
- It's Kim Nam Hee's turn.

1542
01:10:53,920 --> 01:10:55,050
Is there a way to save him...

1543
01:10:55,050 --> 01:10:56,320
- Yes?
- and send her home instead?

1544
01:10:56,490 --> 01:10:57,590
Nam Hee?

1545
01:10:57,850 --> 01:11:00,690
I couldn't believe there was a player
with no manners on this show.

1546
01:11:00,690 --> 01:11:03,760
So I wanted to eliminate her myself.

1547
01:11:03,930 --> 01:11:05,660
Are you targeting me now?

1548
01:11:06,200 --> 01:11:07,560
Are you trying to eliminate me?

1549
01:11:07,930 --> 01:11:09,970
- But I...
- Well, one of us has to get eliminated.

1550
01:11:10,070 --> 01:11:12,300
- Is that so?
- What choice do we have?

1551
01:11:13,400 --> 01:11:15,270
I couldn't control my facial expression.

1552
01:11:17,310 --> 01:11:20,540
He offered us a deal
when Jin Hyeong was in a pickle.

1553
01:11:20,740 --> 01:11:22,580
He said they would help Jin Hyeong
under the condition...

1554
01:11:22,580 --> 01:11:23,880
that we got rid of Nam Hee.

1555
01:11:24,680 --> 01:11:30,750
(For Jin Hyeong to obtain the tile
with 2 yellow and green boxes,)

1556
01:11:31,120 --> 01:11:33,020
(he needs Seung Yong
and Gwan Hee's help...)

1557
01:11:33,020 --> 01:11:34,830
(as they go before him.)

1558
01:11:35,260 --> 01:11:36,530
Things are really bad.

1559
01:11:36,660 --> 01:11:37,860
Those two will go...

1560
01:11:37,860 --> 01:11:39,400
- right before you.
- So...

1561
01:11:39,400 --> 01:11:41,970
- whoever they choose to help...
- Exactly.

1562
01:11:42,130 --> 01:11:44,230
- will decide the game.
- Yes.

1563
01:11:48,370 --> 01:11:49,870
Darn it.

1564
01:11:51,210 --> 01:11:52,440
I'm getting a headache. Wait.

1565
01:11:54,950 --> 01:11:58,150
Do I want to help Jin Hyeong this badly,
to the point...

1566
01:11:59,780 --> 01:12:01,820
that I would betray Nam Hee?

1567
01:12:03,490 --> 01:12:04,590
Right. What will you do?

1568
01:12:04,590 --> 01:12:05,720
- You're going to stop her?
- Wait.

1569
01:12:06,220 --> 01:12:07,290
What?

1570
01:12:07,960 --> 01:12:09,060
The truth was,

1571
01:12:09,430 --> 01:12:12,930
there wasn't a big difference to me
between Jin Hyeong and Nam Hee.

1572
01:12:13,460 --> 01:12:15,300
I'll be completely honest with you.

1573
01:12:15,300 --> 01:12:17,400
Getting Yeon Cheong eliminated
would be the best outcome for me...

1574
01:12:17,400 --> 01:12:18,900
- looking at the scores.
- I see.

1575
01:12:19,670 --> 01:12:21,540
I leaned more toward...

1576
01:12:21,670 --> 01:12:23,370
Nam Hee than the rookies.

1577
01:12:23,370 --> 01:12:25,740
So the deal didn't go through.

1578
01:12:26,140 --> 01:12:28,380
Jin Hyeong and Tae Gyun tried to save her.

1579
01:12:28,580 --> 01:12:30,180
They were a bad judge of character.

1580
01:12:30,380 --> 01:12:32,320
After that, I tried my best...

1581
01:12:32,320 --> 01:12:34,280
to save my team.

1582
01:12:34,720 --> 01:12:37,320
Even if Jin Hyeong were
to move his tiles...

1583
01:12:38,190 --> 01:12:40,320
to maximize the score,

1584
01:12:41,020 --> 01:12:43,090
he would end up around 17 to 19 points.

1585
01:12:43,090 --> 01:12:45,730
- That's all he can get.
- Then let's play it safe.

1586
01:12:45,730 --> 01:12:47,330
- But Nam Hee...
- Let's get him eliminated.

1587
01:12:49,830 --> 01:12:51,770
Did I pick the wrong color
in the beginning?

1588
01:12:53,570 --> 01:12:54,870
Or did I mess up the arrangement?

1589
01:12:59,840 --> 01:13:03,310
Green tiles...
Anyway, here's what our strategy is.

1590
01:13:03,550 --> 01:13:06,350
We must do whatever it takes to stop
Jin Hyeong from taking tiles...

1591
01:13:06,350 --> 01:13:07,680
with two green boxes.

1592
01:13:12,760 --> 01:13:14,260
It's Lee Gwan Hee's turn.

1593
01:13:14,860 --> 01:13:15,930
But...

1594
01:13:17,130 --> 01:13:18,500
- If I take the third one...
- Yes.

1595
01:13:18,500 --> 01:13:19,830
if you take the third one, it's over.
Right?

1596
01:13:19,830 --> 01:13:21,430
(They're trying to ruin the odds
for Yeon Cheong too.)

1597
01:13:21,430 --> 01:13:22,830
- Yes.
- I can take this tile.

1598
01:13:22,830 --> 01:13:25,100
- Yes.
- If you take this, we'd save a turn.

1599
01:13:25,340 --> 01:13:26,500
Should we do that?

1600
01:13:26,500 --> 01:13:28,040
It's Lee Jin Hyeong's turn.

1601
01:13:28,240 --> 01:13:29,510
I'll take it then.

1602
01:13:30,810 --> 01:13:32,510
It's Lee Tae Gyun's turn.

1603
01:13:34,540 --> 01:13:36,450
(Tile Arrangement of Round 11)

1604
01:13:36,450 --> 01:13:38,620
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1605
01:13:44,820 --> 01:13:47,060
So the points are...

1606
01:13:49,360 --> 01:13:50,430
It's tough, right?

1607
01:13:51,290 --> 01:13:52,330
- Hey.
- What?

1608
01:13:52,330 --> 01:13:54,500
- Did you take it?
- They're so stupid.

1609
01:13:54,500 --> 01:13:55,530
They put down the tile...

1610
01:13:55,530 --> 01:13:56,730
with the two green boxes
in the worst place.

1611
01:13:57,130 --> 01:13:58,670
- For whose board?
- Yeon Cheong's.

1612
01:13:59,070 --> 01:14:01,000
Wait. This one...

1613
01:14:01,000 --> 01:14:02,470
What do you think?

1614
01:14:02,470 --> 01:14:04,410
We should've put this one
with the two green boxes here.

1615
01:14:05,210 --> 01:14:07,210
- What?
- This tile should've been here.

1616
01:14:08,210 --> 01:14:09,980
If two boxes were here
and an extra box was here...

1617
01:14:09,980 --> 01:14:12,180
One, two, three, four, five, six, seven.
We could've gotten seven.

1618
01:14:12,320 --> 01:14:13,450
Yeon Cheong...

1619
01:14:13,450 --> 01:14:14,580
(The chosen tile from Round 11)

1620
01:14:14,580 --> 01:14:16,590
I told her to put the tile
with two green boxes on the bottom,

1621
01:14:16,590 --> 01:14:20,720
so she could get seven points
with her secondary color.

1622
01:14:20,720 --> 01:14:24,430
But she listened to Seung Yong
and put it at the top.

1623
01:14:24,430 --> 01:14:25,630
So she only got five points.

1624
01:14:25,630 --> 01:14:27,430
(With his version,
she could've connected 7 green boxes.)

1625
01:14:27,700 --> 01:14:28,870
- He told me to put it here.
- This...

1626
01:14:28,870 --> 01:14:30,370
Why did you put this on the bottom?

1627
01:14:30,630 --> 01:14:32,440
- You two aren't on the same page.
- Why not here?

1628
01:14:32,670 --> 01:14:34,740
Gwan Hee and I had different ideas...

1629
01:14:34,740 --> 01:14:37,370
about arranging the tiles on the board.

1630
01:14:37,470 --> 01:14:39,180
There was a case of miscommunication.

1631
01:14:39,440 --> 01:14:41,680
"Why did you listen to him?"

1632
01:14:42,010 --> 01:14:45,480
By then, I was already out of it.
I couldn't stay focused.

1633
01:14:45,480 --> 01:14:47,350
(Tile Arrangement of Round 12)

1634
01:14:47,350 --> 01:14:50,250
(Yeon Cheong, Nam Hee, Seung Yong,
Gwan Hee, Jin Hyeong, Tae Gyun)

1635
01:14:50,250 --> 01:14:51,620
(Tile Arrangement of Round 13)

1636
01:14:51,620 --> 01:14:53,520
(The players quickly grab
the remaining tiles.)

1637
01:14:55,730 --> 01:14:56,860
Next...

1638
01:14:56,990 --> 01:14:58,560
- Let's do this.
- We got this.

1639
01:14:58,560 --> 01:14:59,700
We can do this.

1640
01:15:01,360 --> 01:15:02,630
It's Lee Tae Gyun's turn.

1641
01:15:03,670 --> 01:15:05,240
(They run out of the tiles.)

1642
01:15:05,240 --> 01:15:07,340
All the tiles have been chosen.

1643
01:15:08,070 --> 01:15:11,070
You will now rearrange your tiles.

1644
01:15:12,140 --> 01:15:14,310
Communication isn't allowed among players.

1645
01:15:14,640 --> 01:15:16,550
The time limit is 30 minutes.

1646
01:15:20,280 --> 01:15:22,550
You can start registering your score now.

1647
01:15:22,750 --> 01:15:24,720
Any player
who wishes to register their score...

1648
01:15:24,890 --> 01:15:28,460
can bring their board to the Voting Room.

1649
01:15:29,060 --> 01:15:31,030
When it comes to games like this,
I'm completely clueless.

1650
01:15:31,030 --> 01:15:33,100
So I needed to save
every second of my time.

1651
01:15:33,100 --> 01:15:35,530
Even if I messed up the rearrangement
and ended up with less than 17 points,

1652
01:15:35,530 --> 01:15:37,470
I registered my score
for a chance to keep 17 points.

1653
01:15:38,540 --> 01:15:40,640
(Lee Jin Hyeong is the first one
to enter.)

1654
01:15:40,640 --> 01:15:41,640
Lee Jin Hyeong.

1655
01:15:41,640 --> 01:15:43,170
- Would you like to register your score?
- Yes.

1656
01:15:44,570 --> 01:15:45,610
Lee Jin Hyeong.

1657
01:15:45,910 --> 01:15:48,880
You have 9 points for yellow
and 8 points for green.

1658
01:15:49,280 --> 01:15:50,680
You registered a total of 17 points.

1659
01:15:50,680 --> 01:15:52,350
Thank you. Bye.

1660
01:15:52,820 --> 01:15:53,880
Lee Tae Gyun.

1661
01:15:54,480 --> 01:15:57,650
You have 15 points for red
and 10 points for blue.

1662
01:15:57,920 --> 01:15:59,760
You registered a total of 25 points.

1663
01:16:00,260 --> 01:16:01,260
Thank you.

1664
01:16:01,260 --> 01:16:02,390
Choi Yeon Cheong.

1665
01:16:02,860 --> 01:16:05,960
You have 13 points for yellow
and 5 points for green.

1666
01:16:06,130 --> 01:16:07,900
You registered a total of 18 points.

1667
01:16:08,100 --> 01:16:09,170
Lee Gwan Hee.

1668
01:16:09,400 --> 01:16:12,570
You have 16 points for blue
and 12 points for yellow.

1669
01:16:12,670 --> 01:16:14,440
You registered a total of 28 points.

1670
01:16:15,370 --> 01:16:16,440
Shin Seung Yong.

1671
01:16:16,810 --> 01:16:19,840
You have 13 points for red
and 8 points for green.

1672
01:16:19,980 --> 01:16:21,780
You registered a total of 21 points.

1673
01:16:22,510 --> 01:16:23,550
Thank you.

1674
01:16:24,010 --> 01:16:25,120
Kim Nam Hee.

1675
01:16:25,320 --> 01:16:28,620
You have 13 points for red
and 11 points for green.

1676
01:16:28,950 --> 01:16:30,820
You registered a total of 24 points.

1677
01:16:31,660 --> 01:16:33,820
(Current scores of Mosaic Puzzle)

1678
01:16:33,820 --> 01:16:36,790
The current lowest score is 17 points.

1679
01:16:37,260 --> 01:16:39,460
(Current lowest score)

1680
01:16:40,260 --> 01:16:42,870
(He starts rearranging the tiles.)

1681
01:16:42,870 --> 01:16:43,870
This way.

1682
01:16:44,800 --> 01:16:46,470
I was losing by a point.

1683
01:16:46,600 --> 01:16:49,010
I was so anxious.
I was ready to give it my all.

1684
01:16:49,440 --> 01:16:51,410
First of all, I tried my best...

1685
01:16:51,410 --> 01:16:54,910
to figure out a way to place
the yellow tile on the top right corner.

1686
01:16:57,810 --> 01:17:01,820
(The more he slides them,
the more the yellow tiles get separated.)

1687
01:17:01,820 --> 01:17:03,450
When I looked at them,
it was a total mess.

1688
01:17:03,950 --> 01:17:05,820
At one point,
it was where I wanted it to be.

1689
01:17:05,820 --> 01:17:07,690
But the rest of the tiles were a mess.

1690
01:17:08,190 --> 01:17:10,160
That's when I started to have
a mental breakdown.

1691
01:17:19,570 --> 01:17:21,370
I didn't know when he could beat my score.

1692
01:17:23,440 --> 01:17:24,940
I kept sliding them.

1693
01:17:25,640 --> 01:17:26,710
I pushed them down
and thought it was wrong,

1694
01:17:26,710 --> 01:17:27,840
so I pushed them back up.

1695
01:17:28,880 --> 01:17:31,250
I tried to connect them.
I didn't want to come last.

1696
01:17:36,720 --> 01:17:39,390
If it had been possible for us...

1697
01:17:40,090 --> 01:17:41,760
to give her advice,

1698
01:17:41,760 --> 01:17:44,460
I would've stayed by her side
and given her advice.

1699
01:17:44,930 --> 01:17:46,130
But we couldn't do that.

1700
01:17:46,130 --> 01:17:49,870
She had to pull herself out of this
on her own.

1701
01:17:50,570 --> 01:17:54,400
I just had to trust her
and let her fight this alone.

1702
01:18:10,450 --> 01:18:13,520
I could see Jin Hyeong's puzzle
from where I was standing.

1703
01:18:13,790 --> 01:18:17,290
In the end,
he had to rearrange the tiles...

1704
01:18:17,290 --> 01:18:20,460
to get additional points in order to win.

1705
01:18:20,760 --> 01:18:22,870
Failing to do that meant he would lose.

1706
01:18:22,870 --> 01:18:26,340
So I was praying that
he would slide his tiles around...

1707
01:18:26,340 --> 01:18:28,200
to make 18 points.

1708
01:18:32,210 --> 01:18:34,240
(Current lowest score)

1709
01:18:34,240 --> 01:18:36,850
I was really anxious
because if I could get another point,

1710
01:18:36,850 --> 01:18:39,120
Yeon Cheong could do the same.

1711
01:18:51,090 --> 01:18:53,860
I was really struggling
to rearrange the tiles for more points.

1712
01:18:53,860 --> 01:18:55,900
I had never played
with sliding puzzles before.

1713
01:18:56,000 --> 01:18:57,330
I know that people...

1714
01:18:57,330 --> 01:18:59,970
who are good at these puzzles know
where to move the pieces.

1715
01:19:00,070 --> 01:19:01,540
But I couldn't do that.

1716
01:19:05,610 --> 01:19:06,840
I was like,
"Am I going to get eliminated today?"

1717
01:19:06,840 --> 01:19:08,040
"Just like that?"

1718
01:19:08,480 --> 01:19:11,450
I just couldn't stop
having these anxious thoughts.

1719
01:19:11,650 --> 01:19:13,420
I was so anxious.

1720
01:19:13,680 --> 01:19:14,980
I couldn't believe it.

1721
01:19:15,990 --> 01:19:17,850
You have ten minutes left.

1722
01:19:17,850 --> 01:19:21,520
(They have 10 minutes left
to rearrange the tiles.)

1723
01:20:02,600 --> 01:20:03,730
Wait...

1724
01:20:10,410 --> 01:20:14,040
(He connected 11 yellow tiles
and 7 green tiles.)

1725
01:20:16,080 --> 01:20:18,880
I kept trying to rearrange the tiles
even if it didn't seem to go anywhere.

1726
01:20:19,150 --> 01:20:22,150
Then at some point,
I managed to get 18 points.

1727
01:20:26,090 --> 01:20:28,160
I thought I was mistaken.

1728
01:20:28,260 --> 01:20:30,390
I counted them 5 or 6 times to make sure.

1729
01:20:37,530 --> 01:20:39,470
Once I counted them ten times,
I knew I had it.

1730
01:20:39,700 --> 01:20:40,840
I had 18 points.

1731
01:20:41,270 --> 01:20:42,570
I definitely had 18 points.

1732
01:20:45,810 --> 01:20:46,840
He got it.

1733
01:20:48,180 --> 01:20:51,050
Jin Hyeong's survival instinct
must have kicked in.

1734
01:20:51,050 --> 01:20:53,650
He kept moving the tiles
with insane focus.

1735
01:20:54,320 --> 01:20:56,520
And he managed to get 18 points.

1736
01:21:09,630 --> 01:21:12,400
Here's what crossed my mind.
If I were to register my board,

1737
01:21:12,400 --> 01:21:14,170
she would find out that
I would have 18 points.

1738
01:21:14,170 --> 01:21:16,370
Then she would work harder
to rearrange her tiles.

1739
01:21:16,370 --> 01:21:17,370
(Current lowest score)

1740
01:21:17,370 --> 01:21:22,380
(The lowest score is revealed
5 minutes before the game ends.)

1741
01:21:22,510 --> 01:21:24,510
Since I managed to find one more point,

1742
01:21:24,510 --> 01:21:26,650
it was possible for her
to find one more point.

1743
01:21:26,980 --> 01:21:29,750
Then I'll be losing in the end.

1744
01:21:29,990 --> 01:21:33,560
I wanted to bluff my card.
So I thought about waiting.

1745
01:21:34,690 --> 01:21:36,290
But to do that,
I didn't have any time left.

1746
01:21:36,530 --> 01:21:38,360
So I registered my score right away.

1747
01:21:39,260 --> 01:21:40,400
Lee Jin Hyeong.

1748
01:21:40,400 --> 01:21:43,170
You have 11 points for yellow
and 7 points for green.

1749
01:21:43,730 --> 01:21:45,570
You registered a total of 18 points.

1750
01:21:47,500 --> 01:21:48,540
Thank you.

1751
01:21:50,770 --> 01:21:53,840
The current lowest score is 18 points.

1752
01:21:55,010 --> 01:21:59,120
(Current lowest score)

1753
01:22:07,560 --> 01:22:09,230
I think I can find more points.

1754
01:22:13,960 --> 01:22:15,700
When I heard the lowest score
was 18 points...

1755
01:22:16,430 --> 01:22:17,970
The score changed because he went in.

1756
01:22:17,970 --> 01:22:20,500
So I tried to move around my tiles
to see what I could do.

1757
01:22:21,140 --> 01:22:23,570
I tried connecting more green tiles
even if I ruined the yellow tiles.

1758
01:22:23,570 --> 01:22:25,140
I tried to see if there were other ways.

1759
01:22:29,380 --> 01:22:32,450
The yellow tiles took
a big part of my board in the middle.

1760
01:22:32,750 --> 01:22:34,680
The moment I moved around other tiles,
I had ruined my yellow chain.

1761
01:22:43,360 --> 01:22:46,030
(Thinking)

1762
01:22:48,530 --> 01:22:49,830
But...

1763
01:22:50,030 --> 01:22:51,800
I had a tile with two green boxes.

1764
01:22:51,970 --> 01:22:54,570
I had a better chance
if they were placed diagonally.

1765
01:22:54,700 --> 01:22:56,010
I figured out a way.

1766
01:22:56,140 --> 01:22:58,210
You have five minutes left.

1767
01:22:59,340 --> 01:23:02,280
The lowest score won't be revealed now.

1768
01:23:04,680 --> 01:23:09,420
(Lee Jin Hyeong's current score,
18 points)

1769
01:23:12,020 --> 01:23:17,430
(Choi Yeon Cheong's lowest score,
18 points)

1770
01:23:19,830 --> 01:23:21,400
Fourteen, fifteen, sixteen, seventeen...

1771
01:23:22,170 --> 01:23:23,270
Eighteen.

1772
01:23:27,170 --> 01:23:28,810
I'll be the first one to get eliminated?

1773
01:23:30,740 --> 01:23:31,980
I can't go home like this.

1774
01:23:36,380 --> 01:23:38,150
The tension was just insane.

1775
01:23:38,720 --> 01:23:39,950
The time was ticking.

1776
01:23:39,950 --> 01:23:42,350
The other players just sat there...

1777
01:23:42,350 --> 01:23:45,090
and watched us with their arms crossed
like we were some monkeys in the zoo.

1778
01:23:45,790 --> 01:23:47,560
My fingers were shaking.
I couldn't focus well.

1779
01:23:47,790 --> 01:23:49,030
I got so sweaty.

1780
01:23:49,030 --> 01:23:51,430
The tiles kept sticking on my palms.

1781
01:23:52,830 --> 01:23:53,930
My gosh.

1782
01:24:01,070 --> 01:24:04,140
The tiles came off
when they got stuck on my palms.

1783
01:24:04,410 --> 01:24:05,440
But...

1784
01:24:05,710 --> 01:24:08,080
(The direction of the tile
had been changed.)

1785
01:24:08,880 --> 01:24:12,050
(The direction of the arranged tiles
can't be changed.)

1786
01:24:29,400 --> 01:24:31,670
You have a minute left.

1787
01:24:34,340 --> 01:24:37,510
I was in big trouble. I was super nervous.

1788
01:24:43,750 --> 01:24:45,780
(Luckily, he was able to rotate the tile.)

1789
01:24:45,780 --> 01:24:50,490
That was the most nerve-racking moment
I had this year.

1790
01:24:51,390 --> 01:24:53,560
You have 30 seconds left.

1791
01:25:16,010 --> 01:25:17,010
I got it.

1792
01:25:33,000 --> 01:25:35,260
The Deathmatch is over.

1793
01:25:37,200 --> 01:25:38,970
(Sighing)

1794
01:25:45,270 --> 01:25:47,640
I'll announce the results
of the Deathmatch.

1795
01:25:48,680 --> 01:25:52,280
The first player to get eliminated
from Bloody Game X is...

1796
01:25:55,250 --> 01:25:57,690
The universe will decide
who wins the Deathmatch.

1797
01:25:57,690 --> 01:26:00,120
I kept a peaceful mind
and prayed while waiting for the results.

1798
01:26:00,390 --> 01:26:03,130
I did my best, and Yeon Cheong
probably did her best too.

1799
01:26:06,560 --> 01:26:08,500
(Choi Yeon Cheong)

1800
01:26:08,600 --> 01:26:12,470
- It's Choi Yeon Cheong.
- Good job.

1801
01:26:12,470 --> 01:26:15,270
Choi Yeon Cheong,
pack up your belongings...

1802
01:26:15,270 --> 01:26:17,610
and leave the Bloody Mansion now.

1803
01:26:19,780 --> 01:26:23,010
(3 minutes before the Deathmatch ended)

1804
01:26:29,550 --> 01:26:33,990
(Choi Yeon Cheong
goes into the Voting Room first.)

1805
01:26:36,660 --> 01:26:38,830
I had to focus on maximizing my points.

1806
01:26:38,830 --> 01:26:40,200
I was busy looking at my board.

1807
01:26:40,200 --> 01:26:42,770
So I tried my best
not to see what she was doing.

1808
01:26:47,300 --> 01:26:49,310
I kept trying to rearrange them
until the last minute.

1809
01:26:53,380 --> 01:26:55,140
I tried to find one more point.

1810
01:26:55,140 --> 01:26:56,850
I was determined
to keep trying until the end.

1811
01:26:58,150 --> 01:26:59,920
I kept counting the tiles.

1812
01:26:59,920 --> 01:27:01,380
And somehow, I ended up with 19 points.

1813
01:27:01,780 --> 01:27:02,790
Four...

1814
01:27:03,320 --> 01:27:05,690
Seven, eleven. Eleven.

1815
01:27:06,320 --> 01:27:09,190
Eleven. Eighteen. Three.

1816
01:27:11,190 --> 01:27:12,200
Hello.

1817
01:27:12,200 --> 01:27:14,430
(He's registering his score
for the third time.)

1818
01:27:15,500 --> 01:27:18,130
Lee Jin Hyeong.
You have 11 points for yellow...

1819
01:27:18,130 --> 01:27:19,570
and eight points for green.

1820
01:27:19,570 --> 01:27:21,370
You registered a total of 19 points.

1821
01:27:21,370 --> 01:27:22,370
Thank you.

1822
01:27:23,170 --> 01:27:24,170
I did it.

1823
01:27:24,440 --> 01:27:26,980
Since I didn't give up and tried my best,

1824
01:27:26,980 --> 01:27:29,850
the universe gave me a nice present.
That's what crossed my mind.

1825
01:27:31,550 --> 01:27:32,550
Well,

1826
01:27:33,920 --> 01:27:35,920
this is my first taste...

1827
01:27:36,920 --> 01:27:37,990
of defeat.

1828
01:27:39,690 --> 01:27:42,560
(She entered the Voting Room
before Jin Hyeong.)

1829
01:27:42,560 --> 01:27:45,660
Is it possible for you
to turn my board back to my initial setup?

1830
01:27:45,960 --> 01:27:47,230
Or do I have to do it myself?

1831
01:27:48,560 --> 01:27:51,770
It's impossible for us to turn it back
to your initial setup.

1832
01:27:52,540 --> 01:27:53,840
They didn't allow it.

1833
01:27:53,840 --> 01:27:56,270
No matter how hard I tried,
the highest score...

1834
01:27:56,270 --> 01:27:58,040
I could get from my board was 18.

1835
01:27:59,240 --> 01:28:01,480
Seven, ten, fifteen.

1836
01:28:02,480 --> 01:28:04,580
I can't find any other connecting tiles.

1837
01:28:08,920 --> 01:28:11,820
Seriously. I had no idea that
I'd be the first one to be eliminated.

1838
01:28:16,630 --> 01:28:17,930
That's why I'm more disappointed.

1839
01:28:17,930 --> 01:28:20,300
I didn't think I would get outsmarted.

1840
01:28:22,500 --> 01:28:25,030
Out here? They expect us to sleep here?

1841
01:28:26,700 --> 01:28:29,310
But I was able to accept my defeat...

1842
01:28:29,570 --> 01:28:32,340
because everyone here
had a great personality.

1843
01:28:32,340 --> 01:28:33,610
I'll do my best.

1844
01:28:33,610 --> 01:28:37,450
We're the losing team.
Why are we worrying about them?

1845
01:28:37,450 --> 01:28:39,980
- Hey. Yes!
- Yes!

1846
01:28:39,980 --> 01:28:41,450
I told you it would work!

1847
01:28:41,450 --> 01:28:44,750
(Team R bonded quickly in one day
on the outdoor survival grounds.)

1848
01:28:44,750 --> 01:28:47,560
Thanks to the three of them,
I was able to...

1849
01:28:48,360 --> 01:28:50,190
survive outdoors.

1850
01:28:51,130 --> 01:28:54,360
I got a great memory out of this.

1851
01:28:56,300 --> 01:28:58,700
I never got to see
the inside of the mansion.

1852
01:29:02,570 --> 01:29:06,540
I thought I ought to prepare myself
a little more next time.

1853
01:29:09,080 --> 01:29:10,180
If there's a next time,

1854
01:29:10,180 --> 01:29:13,850
I'll come prepared
to do whatever it takes to win.

1855
01:29:14,380 --> 01:29:18,720
(The first player to be eliminated,
Choi Yeon Cheong)

1856
01:29:21,220 --> 01:29:23,430
The Deathmatch is over.

1857
01:29:24,490 --> 01:29:26,260
Darn it.

1858
01:29:26,600 --> 01:29:27,730
- Seriously, Jin Hyeong.
- Thank you.

1859
01:29:27,730 --> 01:29:29,130
- Seriously.
- Gosh.

1860
01:29:29,130 --> 01:29:30,570
- All of us survived.
- All of us survived.

1861
01:29:30,570 --> 01:29:32,670
- Who got eliminated then?
- Choi Yeon Cheong.

1862
01:29:32,670 --> 01:29:33,840
The lady.

1863
01:29:34,840 --> 01:29:37,110
Seriously. It was so tough.

1864
01:29:37,170 --> 01:29:38,240
(Team P1's room)

1865
01:29:38,240 --> 01:29:39,240
Guys!

1866
01:29:41,210 --> 01:29:42,210
I'm back.

1867
01:29:44,250 --> 01:29:45,450
It took a long time.

1868
01:29:45,450 --> 01:29:46,780
The game took forever.

1869
01:29:46,780 --> 01:29:48,050
(Team P2's room)

1870
01:29:48,050 --> 01:29:49,050
Guess who.

1871
01:29:49,320 --> 01:29:50,350
Guess who's back.

1872
01:29:50,350 --> 01:29:52,920
- Who won the game?
- Who lost?

1873
01:29:53,320 --> 01:29:54,690
- Really?
- Choi Yeon Cheong.

1874
01:29:55,020 --> 01:29:56,130
- Who?
- Choi Yeon Cheong.

1875
01:29:56,130 --> 01:29:57,230
The girl from outside?

1876
01:29:57,230 --> 01:29:58,960
Well, the thing is...

1877
01:30:00,400 --> 01:30:02,230
- I weaseled my way out of there.
- I knew it.

1878
01:30:02,230 --> 01:30:03,800
- Was it fun?
- That was easy.

1879
01:30:04,170 --> 01:30:05,570
- Congratulations.
- Thank you.

1880
01:30:05,570 --> 01:30:07,100
- I knew you could do it.
- I'm never going back there again.

1881
01:30:07,400 --> 01:30:08,870
- You are...
- The thing is... Yes.

1882
01:30:08,870 --> 01:30:11,210
Chris Evans from "Snowpiercer."
You just cut off your arm.

1883
01:30:11,310 --> 01:30:13,380
- You're Chris Evans.
- Yes. You just cut off your arm.

1884
01:30:13,380 --> 01:30:14,940
- That's so cool.
- So cool.

1885
01:30:16,950 --> 01:30:18,210
Yes!

1886
01:30:18,580 --> 01:30:20,580
Seriously. We were so happy.

1887
01:30:20,820 --> 01:30:22,420
He was reliable,
and I was so proud of him.

1888
01:30:22,690 --> 01:30:25,650
I was able to put down the burden...

1889
01:30:25,650 --> 01:30:29,360
I was carrying when he came back.

1890
01:30:29,890 --> 01:30:31,290
- Anyway, I'll go and eat.
- Go ahead.

1891
01:30:31,290 --> 01:30:32,800
- Enjoy.
- Okay. See you later.

1892
01:30:33,830 --> 01:30:36,500
First of all, Jin Hyeong is so cool.

1893
01:30:37,770 --> 01:30:39,030
- He survived this one.
- He did.

1894
01:30:39,030 --> 01:30:40,140
He showed and proved.

1895
01:30:41,840 --> 01:30:44,610
- Show and prove.
- It's our turn now.

1896
01:30:44,670 --> 01:30:46,380
- No. Now,
- No?

1897
01:30:46,880 --> 01:30:47,880
we're a team.

1898
01:30:52,980 --> 01:30:54,180
Sure, we're on the same team.

1899
01:30:54,180 --> 01:30:55,580
But we had a feeling that...

1900
01:30:55,580 --> 01:30:57,290
- he might come after us at one point.
- Yes.

1901
01:30:57,290 --> 01:30:58,490
Now, he's on our team.

1902
01:30:58,490 --> 01:30:59,760
I'll forgive him for what he did before.

1903
01:31:00,390 --> 01:31:02,120
I can't resent him
for the rest of my life.

1904
01:31:02,120 --> 01:31:03,730
I sent him there
so I could settle my resentment.

1905
01:31:03,830 --> 01:31:05,460
Since he made it back, it's gone now.

1906
01:31:05,630 --> 01:31:08,400
I'll treat Jin Hyeong the same way
I treat YunB.

1907
01:31:08,400 --> 01:31:11,170
I'll treat Seung Jin the same way too.
We've become a real team now.

1908
01:31:11,170 --> 01:31:13,300
I thought he'd never agree to go.
Not only did he agree to go,

1909
01:31:13,300 --> 01:31:14,800
but he also returned as a winner.

1910
01:31:15,070 --> 01:31:16,610
This turned out well for Jin Hyeong.

1911
01:31:16,610 --> 01:31:18,040
And we were happy with that too.

1912
01:31:18,040 --> 01:31:19,040
So it was good for everyone.

1913
01:31:19,040 --> 01:31:21,680
We knew that he'd come back.

1914
01:31:21,880 --> 01:31:23,810
When Jin Hyeong came back,

1915
01:31:23,810 --> 01:31:26,780
I was like,
"Yes, Jin Hyeong settled his bad karma."

1916
01:31:26,780 --> 01:31:28,450
"Jin Hyeong is reborn."

1917
01:31:28,920 --> 01:31:30,550
- Gosh, this was tough.
- Yes.

1918
01:31:30,550 --> 01:31:31,990
- Let's toast.
- We must prepare for the main match.

1919
01:31:31,990 --> 01:31:33,020
Let's just clink our cans.

1920
01:31:33,820 --> 01:31:35,990
Do we have to do the main match too?

1921
01:31:35,990 --> 01:31:36,990
Yes. You have to.

1922
01:31:36,990 --> 01:31:39,600
But it's okay. You get a pass.

1923
01:31:39,600 --> 01:31:42,000
- Treat this as your vacation.
- My vacation?

1924
01:31:42,000 --> 01:31:43,830
- What are you talking about?
- Treat it as your vacation.

1925
01:31:43,830 --> 01:31:46,540
I was very happy that she came back.

1926
01:31:46,540 --> 01:31:49,810
But I was the one who cornered her
into the Deathmatch in the beginning.

1927
01:31:49,810 --> 01:31:52,880
I felt a bit guilty and uneasy about that.

1928
01:31:52,880 --> 01:31:57,710
I prepared a lot of drinks,
so she could have them.

1929
01:31:57,910 --> 01:31:59,150
- Yes.
- This came up too.

1930
01:31:59,150 --> 01:32:01,820
If one of us has to go
to the Deathmatch again,

1931
01:32:01,820 --> 01:32:03,920
someone from the three of us
will go, not you.

1932
01:32:03,920 --> 01:32:05,090
I see.

1933
01:32:05,620 --> 01:32:06,660
We decided to pick...

1934
01:32:06,660 --> 01:32:08,790
someone with the best shot at winning
among us three.

1935
01:32:08,790 --> 01:32:09,860
I see.

1936
01:32:10,160 --> 01:32:11,630
- So...
- You can...

1937
01:32:11,630 --> 01:32:12,800
just relax now.

1938
01:32:12,800 --> 01:32:14,260
- Relax.
- Just relax.

1939
01:32:14,260 --> 01:32:16,070
You'll be safe for two days at least.

1940
01:32:17,270 --> 01:32:19,070
"Nam Hee,
you won't go to the Deathmatch now."

1941
01:32:19,070 --> 01:32:20,500
"We'll take turns to go."

1942
01:32:20,500 --> 01:32:22,370
"You don't have to go again."
That's what they said.

1943
01:32:23,040 --> 01:32:24,240
But I couldn't trust them.

1944
01:32:24,240 --> 01:32:26,240
They stabbed me in the back.

1945
01:32:26,240 --> 01:32:27,580
So I couldn't trust them.

1946
01:32:27,580 --> 01:32:30,750
To be honest, my mood didn't improve
quickly when I went back.

1947
01:32:31,980 --> 01:32:33,820
Please gather in the main hall.

1948
01:32:34,220 --> 01:32:36,190
He went for it. He was quite good at it.

1949
01:32:36,720 --> 01:32:38,450
What does your shirt say?

1950
01:32:38,750 --> 01:32:41,220
Ji Min. That's...

1951
01:32:41,290 --> 01:32:43,960
(Survival is proof of strength.)

1952
01:32:44,260 --> 01:32:46,230
Ji Min. That's...

1953
01:32:46,230 --> 01:32:47,560
He switched seats with me too.

1954
01:32:48,100 --> 01:32:49,100
I shouldn't block his shirt.

1955
01:32:49,100 --> 01:32:50,130
Because he survived the Deathmatch?

1956
01:32:50,130 --> 01:32:51,370
- Yes. He has to show it.
- Gosh, Jin Hyeong.

1957
01:32:51,370 --> 01:32:53,000
- To show off.
- You came fully prepared.

1958
01:32:53,000 --> 01:32:54,070
You have no idea.

1959
01:32:55,570 --> 01:32:57,070
- Hello.
- Hello.

1960
01:32:57,070 --> 01:32:58,070
Hello.

1961
01:32:59,840 --> 01:33:01,580
- Good job.
- Gwan Hee.

1962
01:33:01,580 --> 01:33:02,680
Good job.

1963
01:33:04,280 --> 01:33:06,250
- Gosh, you made it.
- Yes.

1964
01:33:06,250 --> 01:33:07,250
Hello.

1965
01:33:08,420 --> 01:33:09,590
What?

1966
01:33:09,590 --> 01:33:11,750
- What is it?
- Kwak Beom is here.

1967
01:33:11,750 --> 01:33:12,790
What? He's here.

1968
01:33:13,660 --> 01:33:14,660
What?

1969
01:33:14,820 --> 01:33:16,190
Welcome.

1970
01:33:19,230 --> 01:33:20,630
- Hello.
- Hi.

1971
01:33:20,630 --> 01:33:21,630
Hello.

1972
01:33:22,930 --> 01:33:24,230
What happened?

1973
01:33:24,230 --> 01:33:25,570
Garlic... It's nothing.

1974
01:33:25,970 --> 01:33:28,440
- No. Don't smell it.
- Come here.

1975
01:33:28,870 --> 01:33:32,580
Appearance-wise, his hair was so oily.

1976
01:33:32,780 --> 01:33:34,180
He smelled like garlic too.

1977
01:33:34,310 --> 01:33:36,280
His clothes were tattered.

1978
01:33:36,450 --> 01:33:39,010
They were stained and soiled.

1979
01:33:39,010 --> 01:33:41,720
I thought I wouldn't have survived
if I ended up there yesterday.

1980
01:33:42,250 --> 01:33:43,890
Gosh, he came here.

1981
01:33:46,460 --> 01:33:48,060
Gosh, I don't feel good about this.

1982
01:33:49,460 --> 01:33:50,660
Good work.

1983
01:33:50,660 --> 01:33:52,090
- We lost.
- What?

1984
01:33:52,090 --> 01:33:53,760
- We lost. I'm sorry.
- Gosh.

1985
01:33:55,230 --> 01:33:56,470
Oh, that's awful.

1986
01:33:57,330 --> 01:33:58,400
We lost.

1987
01:33:58,400 --> 01:34:02,040
When I walked in,
I saw Gwan Hee and Seung Yong.

1988
01:34:02,340 --> 01:34:03,770
I didn't see Yeon Cheong.

1989
01:34:03,770 --> 01:34:05,070
I knew she got eliminated then.

1990
01:34:06,040 --> 01:34:07,510
How did it happen?

1991
01:34:08,180 --> 01:34:09,510
- It was an individual match.
- What?

1992
01:34:09,510 --> 01:34:11,180
It wasn't a team match.
It was an individual match.

1993
01:34:11,950 --> 01:34:14,380
- What? Really?
- The six of us were all on our own.

1994
01:34:14,750 --> 01:34:16,390
She lost. We tried our best...

1995
01:34:16,790 --> 01:34:18,190
- to help her.
- Okay.

1996
01:34:18,190 --> 01:34:20,020
But he beat her at the last moment.

1997
01:34:20,020 --> 01:34:22,290
It was impossible to play as a team?

1998
01:34:22,290 --> 01:34:23,960
We could play as a team.

1999
01:34:23,960 --> 01:34:26,730
- But we were on our own at the end.
- Gwan Hee.

2000
01:34:26,730 --> 01:34:30,400
I felt so terrible that
I couldn't face Beom.

2001
01:34:31,130 --> 01:34:32,500
I was too ashamed to face him.

2002
01:34:33,040 --> 01:34:36,970
We just wanted to play a game together
as a team.

2003
01:34:36,970 --> 01:34:39,270
We only spent a few hours together,
but I had grown fond of her.

2004
01:34:39,270 --> 01:34:41,240
Hearing that she was eliminated
was disappointing.

2005
01:34:41,240 --> 01:34:42,910
I volunteered to go,
but they decided to go.

2006
01:34:42,910 --> 01:34:44,250
That's how she got eliminated.

2007
01:34:44,250 --> 01:34:46,920
Part of me was happy to see that
they had been wrong, to be honest.

2008
01:34:48,520 --> 01:34:51,020
Look at her. She's drinking now?

2009
01:34:53,390 --> 01:34:54,990
Just stay here a little longer.
You can't survive without drinks.

2010
01:34:54,990 --> 01:34:57,430
I only had half of a potato.

2011
01:34:57,430 --> 01:34:58,790
We have food over there.

2012
01:34:58,790 --> 01:34:59,800
- Where?
- There's food.

2013
01:34:59,800 --> 01:35:00,830
- Go ahead.
- We have plenty of food.

2014
01:35:00,830 --> 01:35:02,460
We can eat that?

2015
01:35:04,000 --> 01:35:05,000
Come here.

2016
01:35:05,130 --> 01:35:07,640
Help yourself to some food.

2017
01:35:08,070 --> 01:35:09,240
My gosh.

2018
01:35:13,210 --> 01:35:14,640
Go ahead and eat. Did you eat?

2019
01:35:18,050 --> 01:35:19,050
My gosh.

2020
01:35:19,450 --> 01:35:21,250
It must've been so tough.

2021
01:35:21,880 --> 01:35:23,920
Here's an announcement.

2022
01:35:24,450 --> 01:35:26,560
A representative of Team Rookie,

2023
01:35:26,560 --> 01:35:29,790
the losing team
of the high-speed team game,

2024
01:35:30,090 --> 01:35:33,300
must proceed to the Voting Room
to check their team fund.

2025
01:35:34,400 --> 01:35:35,400
I'll go.

2026
01:35:39,370 --> 01:35:42,810
Team Rookie, you were the losing team
of the high-speed team game.

2027
01:35:42,810 --> 01:35:44,940
According to the rules of the game,

2028
01:35:44,940 --> 01:35:47,240
your team was left with...

2029
01:35:47,240 --> 01:35:50,050
the unchosen funds of Team P2 by default.

2030
01:35:52,980 --> 01:35:54,180
Why is there so much money?

2031
01:35:55,820 --> 01:35:56,820
This is a lot.

2032
01:35:57,590 --> 01:36:01,220
Team P2's fund is 180,000 dollars.

2033
01:36:01,790 --> 01:36:05,460
Team Rookie's team fund became
180,000 dollars just now.

2034
01:36:06,160 --> 01:36:07,230
(Team P2)

2035
01:36:07,230 --> 01:36:08,900
(200,000 dollars, 140,000 dollars,
100,000 dollars, 7,500 dollars)

2036
01:36:08,900 --> 01:36:10,430
(70,000 dollars, 50,000 dollars,
50,000 dollars, 10,000 dollars)

2037
01:36:10,430 --> 01:36:14,440
(Team R's fund: 180,000 dollars)

2038
01:36:14,800 --> 01:36:17,240
If we end up
on the outdoor survival grounds,

2039
01:36:17,840 --> 01:36:20,180
I asked Seung Jin to hit me,
so I'd be unconscious for 12 hours.

2040
01:36:20,180 --> 01:36:22,980
One of the teams must go there.

2041
01:36:23,850 --> 01:36:27,420
Here are the benefits for the winning team
of today's Money Challenge.

2042
01:36:28,350 --> 01:36:30,490
The winning team
of today's Money Challenge...

2043
01:36:30,990 --> 01:36:33,190
will get 500,000 dollars.

2044
01:36:33,520 --> 01:36:35,260
All of them will be exempt
from elimination.

2045
01:36:35,560 --> 01:36:39,030
And they will be given
an extra vote ticket.

2046
01:36:39,030 --> 01:36:40,330
I see. An extra vote ticket?

2047
01:36:40,960 --> 01:36:43,230
The team that comes in second...

2048
01:36:43,430 --> 01:36:45,930
will also be exempt from elimination.

2049
01:36:46,370 --> 01:36:48,170
Second place won't get eliminated either.

2050
01:36:48,770 --> 01:36:51,040
Moreover, the losing team...

2051
01:36:51,040 --> 01:36:54,410
will be kicked out
to the outdoor survival grounds.

2052
01:36:54,780 --> 01:36:58,280
Today's Money Challenge
will be revealed now.

2053
01:36:58,810 --> 01:37:00,680
Today's Money Challenge is called...

2054
01:37:02,650 --> 01:37:05,550
Mystery Time.

2055
01:37:06,390 --> 01:37:08,490
Today's Money Challenge is Mystery Time.

2056
01:37:08,490 --> 01:37:11,090
- Gosh.
- You did it, didn't you?

2057
01:37:11,630 --> 01:37:14,000
What? I played this before.

2058
01:37:14,160 --> 01:37:16,430
I came in first place before.

2059
01:37:16,430 --> 01:37:18,730
I came in 1st place 2 times.
3 times will be easy.

2060
01:37:18,730 --> 01:37:22,070
Most of my team members
have played that game before.

2061
01:37:22,240 --> 01:37:23,610
What's more, it's Mystery Time Two.

2062
01:37:23,610 --> 01:37:24,610
We were in Mystery Time One.

2063
01:37:24,610 --> 01:37:26,180
I had a good feeling about it.

2064
01:37:26,180 --> 01:37:27,910
I had high hopes.

2065
01:37:28,240 --> 01:37:31,380
Mystery Time will be played
with five teams.

2066
01:37:31,710 --> 01:37:33,880
Using your reasoning skills and judgement,

2067
01:37:34,120 --> 01:37:37,590
you must infer the cause and effect
of the given case.

2068
01:37:38,190 --> 01:37:41,320
The case is fictitious
and unrelated to reality.

2069
01:37:41,320 --> 01:37:43,890
All characters, background,

2070
01:37:43,890 --> 01:37:46,400
and details are entirely fictional.

2071
01:37:46,960 --> 01:37:49,460
You will play a total of two rounds.

2072
01:37:50,130 --> 01:37:52,840
In Round 1, all 5 teams will take part.

2073
01:37:53,270 --> 01:37:55,940
In Round 2, the remaining 4 teams,
excluding the winner of Round 1,

2074
01:37:55,940 --> 01:37:57,540
will take part.

2075
01:37:58,340 --> 01:37:59,810
Once the round begins,

2076
01:37:59,910 --> 01:38:01,310
the question, image,

2077
01:38:01,310 --> 01:38:03,380
and the answer's number of keywords
are revealed.

2078
01:38:03,780 --> 01:38:07,120
At the same time,
every player's time starts ticking.

2079
01:38:08,280 --> 01:38:11,750
The players can do
two of the following in the Voting Room.

2080
01:38:12,550 --> 01:38:14,990
First, ask questions.

2081
01:38:15,620 --> 01:38:18,860
A player can ask up to 3 questions
in 1 visit.

2082
01:38:19,160 --> 01:38:21,030
One minute is added...

2083
01:38:21,030 --> 01:38:24,130
to the player's time with each question.

2084
01:38:24,770 --> 01:38:27,740
If all the questions are true,
the butler will answer,

2085
01:38:28,070 --> 01:38:29,470
"Yes, that is correct."

2086
01:38:30,070 --> 01:38:31,710
If all are false, the butler will answer,

2087
01:38:31,710 --> 01:38:33,580
"No, that is incorrect."

2088
01:38:34,180 --> 01:38:36,610
If there are both true and false,

2089
01:38:36,610 --> 01:38:38,250
or if the answer is unclear,

2090
01:38:38,250 --> 01:38:39,650
the butler will answer, "Maybe."

2091
01:38:40,320 --> 01:38:42,750
If it's not important
to solving the question,

2092
01:38:42,750 --> 01:38:45,290
the butler will answer,
"It is not important."

2093
01:38:45,920 --> 01:38:48,490
Second, guess the answer.

2094
01:38:49,220 --> 01:38:51,960
If the cause and effect of the case
is correct...

2095
01:38:51,960 --> 01:38:54,960
and all keywords are included,

2096
01:38:55,100 --> 01:38:56,130
you will get a "correct."

2097
01:38:56,600 --> 01:38:58,570
If there is incorrect information,

2098
01:38:58,570 --> 01:39:00,000
you will get an "incorrect."

2099
01:39:00,370 --> 01:39:02,500
If the cause and effect is correct...

2100
01:39:02,500 --> 01:39:05,010
but the keywords are incomplete,

2101
01:39:05,010 --> 01:39:07,080
you will get a "missing keyword."

2102
01:39:07,080 --> 01:39:08,080
(Missing keyword)

2103
01:39:08,210 --> 01:39:09,950
If you fail to get the answer,

2104
01:39:10,110 --> 01:39:12,450
five minutes will be added
to the player's time.

2105
01:39:13,220 --> 01:39:14,620
If you get the answer,

2106
01:39:14,620 --> 01:39:17,720
the time will stop
for all players on the team.

2107
01:39:18,050 --> 01:39:20,360
When 30 minutes have passed
since the game started,

2108
01:39:20,620 --> 01:39:22,420
the Time Room will open.

2109
01:39:23,030 --> 01:39:26,560
In the Time Room,
one image hint is revealed.

2110
01:39:26,960 --> 01:39:30,270
A new hint is revealed every 30 minutes.

2111
01:39:30,930 --> 01:39:33,100
The moment a player enters the Time Room,

2112
01:39:33,100 --> 01:39:36,340
their time will pass twice as fast.

2113
01:39:36,740 --> 01:39:39,640
Only one player from each team
can enter the room.

2114
01:39:40,010 --> 01:39:42,540
In the room, no notes can be taken.

2115
01:39:43,250 --> 01:39:45,950
Once a team gets the correct answer
in Round One,

2116
01:39:45,950 --> 01:39:47,820
the game ends immediately.

2117
01:39:47,820 --> 01:39:50,490
That team will finish in first place,

2118
01:39:50,490 --> 01:39:52,550
get an elimination immunity pass
for all team members,

2119
01:39:52,750 --> 01:39:54,620
and will not participate in Round Two.

2120
01:39:56,330 --> 01:39:57,930
Before Round Two,

2121
01:39:57,930 --> 01:39:59,490
the accumulated time
of the remaining four teams...

2122
01:39:59,490 --> 01:40:00,930
will be revealed.

2123
01:40:01,300 --> 01:40:03,030
Round Two will resume from that time...

2124
01:40:03,030 --> 01:40:06,230
and proceed in the same manner
as Round One.

2125
01:40:07,000 --> 01:40:08,300
In Round Two,

2126
01:40:08,540 --> 01:40:11,010
starting 30 minutes
after the Time Room closes,

2127
01:40:11,010 --> 01:40:14,010
new sentence hints
will be revealed every 30 minutes.

2128
01:40:14,010 --> 01:40:16,110
(Extra hint 1, Extra hint 2, Extra hint 3)

2129
01:40:16,110 --> 01:40:18,580
The team
to get the correct answer first...

2130
01:40:18,580 --> 01:40:20,320
will finish in second place...

2131
01:40:20,320 --> 01:40:22,750
and get an elimination immunity pass
for all team members.

2132
01:40:22,950 --> 01:40:25,390
The remaining teams will finish...

2133
01:40:25,390 --> 01:40:28,420
in 3rd and 4th place
in order of getting the answer correct.

2134
01:40:29,190 --> 01:40:30,860
The team that doesn't get the answer...

2135
01:40:30,860 --> 01:40:33,060
will finish in fifth place.

2136
01:40:34,000 --> 01:40:35,260
After the game,

2137
01:40:35,260 --> 01:40:39,230
the player with the most accumulated time
from the fifth-place team...

2138
01:40:39,230 --> 01:40:40,970
will go to the Deathmatch.

2139
01:40:41,370 --> 01:40:43,270
From 3rd- and 4th-place teams,

2140
01:40:43,270 --> 01:40:46,580
the players
with the least accumulated time...

2141
01:40:46,580 --> 01:40:49,280
will become elimination candidates,
and a vote will take place.

2142
01:40:50,150 --> 01:40:52,050
The voted player...

2143
01:40:52,050 --> 01:40:54,150
and the Deathmatch player...

2144
01:40:54,150 --> 01:40:56,320
will play a 1-on-1 Deathmatch.

2145
01:40:56,650 --> 01:41:00,860
The loser is eliminated
from Bloody Game X.

2146
01:41:02,120 --> 01:41:05,560
There are three items in Mystery Time.

2147
01:41:06,230 --> 01:41:09,930
The first item is
the image hint replay pass.

2148
01:41:10,700 --> 01:41:12,670
The player can check...

2149
01:41:12,670 --> 01:41:14,970
one of the hints revealed
in the Time Room again.

2150
01:41:16,040 --> 01:41:19,110
The second item is
the keyword reveal pass.

2151
01:41:19,640 --> 01:41:22,810
The player can check whether one keyword
is correct or incorrect.

2152
01:41:23,510 --> 01:41:26,520
The third item is a hidden item.

2153
01:41:26,980 --> 01:41:30,020
It will be revealed 80 minutes
after Round 1 begins.

2154
01:41:30,590 --> 01:41:32,550
I'm a big fan of mystery novels.

2155
01:41:32,550 --> 01:41:34,560
I've read
many of Keigo Higashino's books...

2156
01:41:34,560 --> 01:41:37,790
as well as classic and modern novels.
I'm a devoted reader.

2157
01:41:37,790 --> 01:41:41,800
Figuring out the case's outline
won't be that hard for me.

2158
01:41:42,000 --> 01:41:43,870
I've been wanting to play this game.

2159
01:41:43,870 --> 01:41:46,170
As I'm a police officer,

2160
01:41:46,170 --> 01:41:48,700
I've heard and witnessed
many criminal cases.

2161
01:41:48,700 --> 01:41:50,770
How about I do some detective work?

2162
01:41:51,340 --> 01:41:52,910
It's my kind of game.

2163
01:41:53,340 --> 01:41:54,780
I'm the MC of "Surprise: Mystery Salon."

2164
01:41:55,080 --> 01:41:59,450
I introduce strange events
and incidents every week.

2165
01:41:59,650 --> 01:42:01,480
It's a game I'm confident about.

2166
01:42:02,580 --> 01:42:06,890
The 30-minute strategy meeting
before the game begins now.

2167
01:42:07,390 --> 01:42:08,860
"Case Closed."

2168
01:42:08,860 --> 01:42:10,330
I love games like this.

2169
01:42:10,330 --> 01:42:11,560
It's something I'm great at.

2170
01:42:11,990 --> 01:42:12,990
This game's mine.

2171
01:42:13,230 --> 01:42:14,930
It's mine. I can show everyone...

2172
01:42:15,160 --> 01:42:16,570
